# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: africa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] The **11th Dynasty** of ancient Egypt (notated **Dynasty XI**; c.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] 1991 BC) is a well-attested group of rulers.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Its earlier members before King Mentuhotep II are grouped with the four preceding dynasties to form the First Intermediate Period, whereas the later members are considered part of the Middle Kingdom.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] They all ruled from Thebes in Upper Egypt.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] The relative chronology of the 11th Dynasty is well established by contemporary attestations and, except for count Intef and Mentuhotep IV, by the Turin canon.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Manetho's statement that the 11th Dynasty consisted of 16 kings, who reigned for 43 years is contradicted by contemporary inscriptions and the evidence of the Turin King List, whose combined testimony establishes that this kingdom consisted of seven kings who ruled for a total of 143 years.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] However, his testimony that this dynasty was based at Thebes is verified by the contemporary evidence.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] It was during this dynasty that all of ancient Egypt was united under the Middle Kingdom.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] This dynasty traces its origins to a nomarch of Thebes, "Intef the Great, son of Iku", who is mentioned in a number of contemporary inscriptions.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] However, his immediate successor Mentuhotep I is considered the first king of this dynasty.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] An inscription carved during the reign of Wahankh Intef II shows that he was the first of this dynasty to claim to rule over the whole of Egypt, a claim which brought the Thebans into conflict with the 10th-Dynasty rulers of Herakleopolis Magna.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Intef undertook several campaigns northwards, and captured the important nome of Abydos.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Warfare continued intermittently between the Theban and Heracleapolitan dynasts until shortly before the 39th regnal year of Nebhepetre Mentuhotep II, when the Herakleopolitans were defeated, and this dynasty could begin to consolidate their rule.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] The rulers of the 11th Dynasty reasserted Egypt's influence over her neighbors in Africa and the Near East.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Mentuhotep II sent renewed expeditions to Phoenicia to obtain cedar.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Sankhkare Mentuhotep III sent an expedition from Coptos south to the land of Punt.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] The reign of its last king, and thus the end of this dynasty, is something of a mystery.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Contemporary records refer to "seven empty years" following the death of Mentuhotep III, which correspond to the reign of Nebtawyre Mentuhotep IV.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Modern scholars identify his vizier Amenemhat with Amenemhat I, the first king of 12th Dynasty, as part of a theory that Amenemhat became king as part of a palace coup.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] The only certain details of Mentuhotep's reign was that two remarkable omens were witnessed at the quarry of Wadi Hammamat by the vizier Amenemhat.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Nobody knows for certain how Amenemhat I rose to power and became the next king.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Kings Mentuhotep II and Mentuhotep III are the most commonly included kings of this dynasty to appear on Egyptian king lists, while their successor Mentuhotep IV was often ignored.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Several names are lost and damaged, but can still be reconstructed.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Some of them like Mentuhotep I and the Intef pharaohs are accompanied by their Horus name, though some of them are damaged.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] The Turin King List begins this dynasty with Mentuhotep I and provides reign lengths for individual kings, however it is in a fragmentary state and some information is now lost.
[src:africa/11th-dynasty] Mentuhotep IV is not mentioned at all, but the list does note "a lacuna of 7 years" following Mentuhotep III.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The **Twelfth Dynasty** of ancient Egypt (**Dynasty XII**) is a series of rulers reigning from c.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] 190 years), at what is often considered to be the apex of the Middle Kingdom (Dynasties XI–XIV).
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The dynasty periodically expanded its territory from the Nile Delta and valley South beyond the second cataract and East into Canaan.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The Twelfth Dynasty was marked by relative stability and development.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] It has a notably well recorded history for the period.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Its first pharaoh was Amenemhat I and its final was Sobekneferu.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The chronology of the Twelfth Dynasty is the most stable of any period before the New Kingdom.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Manetho stated that it was based in Thebes, but from contemporary records it is clear that the first king of this dynasty, Amenemhat I, moved its capital to a new city named "Amenemhat-itj-tawy" ("Amenemhat the Seizer of the Two Lands"), more simply called, Itjtawy.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The location of Itjtawy has not been discovered yet, but it is thought to be near the Fayyum, probably near the royal graveyards at el-Lisht.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The order of its rulers of the Twelfth Dynasty is well known from several sources: two lists recorded at temples in Abydos and one at Saqqara, as well as lists derived from Manetho's work.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] A recorded date during the reign of Senusret III can be correlated to the Sothic cycle, consequently, many events during this dynasty frequently can be assigned to a specific year.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] However, scholars now have expressed skepticism in the usefulness of the referred date, due to the fact that location affects observation of the Sothic cycle.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Egypt underwent various developments under the Twelfth Dynasty, including the reorganization of the kingdom's administration and agricultural developments in the Fayyum.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The Twelfth Dynasty was also responsible for significant expansion of Egyptian borders, with campaigns pushing into Nubia and the Levant.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The Twelfth Dynasty is often considered the apex of Egypt's Middle Kingdom.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The Middle Kingdom spans the Eleventh, Thirteenth, and Fourteenth dynasties, but some scholars only consider the 11th and 12th dynasties to be part of the Middle Kingdom.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] This dynasty was founded by Amenemhat I, who may have been vizier to the last king of Dynasty XI, Mentuhotep IV.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] His armies campaigned south as far as the Second Cataract of the Nile and into southern Canaan.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] As a part of his militaristic expansion of Egypt, Amenemhat I ordered the construction of multiple military forts in Nubia.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] He also reestablished diplomatic relations with the Canaanite state of Byblos and Hellenic rulers in the Aegean Sea.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] For the first ten years of his reign, Senusret I possibly ruled as a coregent alongside his father, Amenemhat I.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] He continued his fathers campaigns into Nubia, expanding Egyptian control to the Third Cataract of the Nile.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] In addition to pursuing militaristic expansion, Senusret I was also responsible for internal growth within Egypt.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] As king, he initiated a considerable amount of building projects across Egypt, including pyramids in Lisht, a temple at Karnak and oversaw the renovation of the kingdom's major temples.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Unlike his predecessors, Amenemhat II was king during a time of peace.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Under his reign, trade boomed with other states in Asia, the Mediterranean, and Africa.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] He built his mortuary complex near Memphis at Dahshur.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Senusret II also reigned during a time of peace.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] He was the first king to develop the Fayyum Basin for agricultural production.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] This development was complex, requiring the digging of several canals and the draining of a lake in order to maximize the Fayyum's agricultural output.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The Middle Kingdom development of the Fayyum later became the basis for the Ptolemaic and Roman efforts that turned the region into the bread basket of the Mediterranean.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Finding Nubia had grown restive under the previous rulers, Senusret sent punitive expeditions into that land.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] As a part of his effort to subdue Nubia, he ordered the construction of several new fortresses as well as the expansion of existing ones along the border with Nubia.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] He also sent an expedition into the Levant.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Senusret III's military career contributed to his prestige during the New Kingdom, as he was regarded as a warrior king and even revered as a god in Nubia.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] One of Senusret III's significant internal developments was the centralization of administrative power in the kingdom, which replaced the nome system with three large administrative districts that encompassed all of Egypt.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Senusret's successor Amenemhat III reaffirmed his predecessor's foreign policy.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] However, after Amenemhat, the energies of this dynasty were largely spent, and the growing troubles of government were left to the dynasty's last ruler, Sobekneferu, to resolve.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Amenemhat was remembered for the mortuary temple at Hawara that he built.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Amenemhat IV succeeded his father, Amenemhat III, and ruled for approximately nine years.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] At the time of his death, Amenemhat IV had no apparent heir, leading to Sobekneferu's ascension to the throne.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Sobekneferu, a daughter of Amenemhat III, was the first known woman to become king of Egypt.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] She was left with the unresolved governmental issues that are noted as arising during her father's reign when she succeeded Amenemhat IV, thought to be her brother, half brother, or step brother.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Upon his death, she became the heir to the throne because her older sister, Neferuptah, who would have been the next in line to rule, died at an early age.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Sobekneferu was the last king of the twelfth dynasty.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] There is no record of her having an heir.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] She also had a relatively short nearly four-year reign and the next dynasty began with a shift in succession, possibly to unrelated heirs of Amenemhat IV.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Several famous works of Egyptian literature originated from the 12th Dynasty.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Perhaps the best known work from this period is *The Story of Sinuhe*, of which papyrus copies dating as late as the New Kingdom have been recovered.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Some of the existing literature pertaining to the 12th Dynasty are propagandistic in nature.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The *Prophecy of Neferti* establishes a revisionist account of history that legitimizes Amenemhat I's rule.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Written during the reign of Amenemhat I, described a sage's prophecy given to the 4th Dynasty King Snefru that predicted a destructive civil war.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] It writes that the sage, Neferti, prophesied that a great king named Ameny (Amenemhat I) would lead a united Egypt out of this tumultuous period.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The work also mentions Amenemhat I's mother being from the Elephantine Egyptian nome Ta-Seti.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Many scholars in recent years have argued that Amenemhat I's mother was of Nubian origin.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] During the Middle Kingdom, under Amenemhat III, textual records show that coerced laborers included conscripts (*hsbw*), fugitives (*tsjw*), and royal laborers (*hmw-nsw*).
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The Reisner Papyrus and El Lahun papyri depict prisoners being employed in state enterprises.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Papyrus Brooklyn 35.1446 also shows forced labor being performed on arable state land.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] Slaves, from neighbouring locations including Nubia, Syria-Palestine but especially of Levantine origin were grouped in ghetto camps to perform labor for the state where they lived in harsh conditions, often including beating by their masters.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The term for "male Asiatic" in ancient Egyptian language became synonymous with "slave".
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The Twelfth Dynasty is well-recorded across Egyptian king lists, which are in broad agreement on the order of the kings in this dynasty.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The surviving Karnak, Abydos and Saqqara king lists, all from the New Kingdom of Egypt, provide a list of kings of this dynasty, though the Abydos list omits Sobekneferu.
[src:africa/12th-dynasty] The Turin King List originally provided individual reign lengths, but is now in a fragmentary state and some information is lost, though the summation of years for this dynasty still survives.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The **Eighteenth Dynasty of Egypt** (notated **Dynasty XVIII**, alternatively **18th Dynasty** or **Dynasty 18**) is classified as the first dynasty of the New Kingdom of Egypt, the era in which ancient Egypt achieved the peak of its power.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The Eighteenth Dynasty spanned the period from 1550/1549 to 1292 BC.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] This dynasty is also known as the **Thutmoside Dynasty** for the four pharaohs named Thutmose.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Several of Egypt's most famous pharaohs were from the Eighteenth Dynasty, including Tutankhamun (c.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Other famous pharaohs of the dynasty include Hatshepsut (c.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] 1479 BC–1458 BC), the longest-reigning woman pharaoh of an indigenous dynasty, and Akhenaten (c.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] 1353–1336 BC), the "heretic pharaoh", with his Great Royal Wife, Nefertiti.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The Eighteenth Dynasty is unique among indigenous Egyptian dynasties in that it had two queens regnant women who ruled as pharaohs: Hatshepsut and Neferneferuaten, usually identified as Nefertiti.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Dynasty XVIII was founded by Ahmose I, the brother or son of Kamose, the last ruler of the 17th Dynasty.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Ahmose finished the campaign to expel the Hyksos rulers.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] His reign is seen as the end of the Second Intermediate Period and the start of the New Kingdom.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Ahmose's consort, Queen Ahmose-Nefertari was "arguably the most venerated woman in Egyptian history, and the grandmother of the 18th Dynasty." She was deified after she died.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Ahmose was succeeded by his son, Amenhotep I, whose reign was relatively uneventful.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep I probably left no male heir and the next pharaoh, Thutmose I, seems to have been related to the royal family through marriage.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] During his reign, the borders of Egypt's empire reached their greatest expanse, extending in the north to Carchemish on the Euphrates and in the south up to Kanisah Kurgus beyond the fourth cataract of the Nile.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Thutmose I was succeeded by Thutmose II and his queen, Hatshepsut, who was the daughter of Thutmose I.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] After her husband's death and a period of regency for her minor stepson (who would later become pharaoh as Thutmose III) Hatshepsut became pharaoh in her own right and ruled for over twenty years.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Thutmose III, who became known as the greatest military pharaoh ever, also had a lengthy reign after becoming pharaoh.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] He had a second co-regency in his old age with his son Amenhotep II.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep II was succeeded by Thutmose IV, who in his turn was followed by his son Amenhotep III, whose reign is seen as a high point in this dynasty.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep III's reign was a period of unprecedented prosperity, artistic splendor, and international power, as attested by over 250 statues (more than any other pharaoh) and 200 large stone scarabs discovered from Syria to Nubia.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep III undertook large scale building programmes, the extent of which can only be compared with those of the much longer reign of Ramesses II during Dynasty XIX.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep III's consort was the Great Royal Wife Tiye, for whom he built an artificial lake, as described on eleven scarabs.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep III may have shared the throne for up to twelve years with his son Amenhotep IV.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] There is much debate about this proposed co-regency, with different experts considering that there was a lengthy co-regency, a short one, or none at all.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] In the fifth year of his reign, Amenhotep IV changed his name to Akhenaten (*ꜣḫ-n-jtn*, "Effective for the Aten") and moved his capital to Amarna, which he named Akhetaten.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] During the reign of Akhenaten, the Aten (jtn, the sun disk) became, first, the most prominent deity, and eventually came to be considered the only god.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Whether this amounted to true monotheism continues to be the subject of debate within the academic community.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Some state that Akhenaten created a monotheism, while others point out that he merely suppressed a dominant solar cult by the assertion of another, while he never completely abandoned several other traditional deities.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Later Egyptians considered this "Amarna Period" an unfortunate aberration.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] After his death, Akhenaten was succeeded by two short-lived pharaohs, Smenkhkare and Neferneferuaten, of which little is known.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] In 1334 BC, Akhenaten's probable son, Tutankhaten, ascended to the throne: shortly after, he restored Egyptian polytheist cult and subsequently changed his name to Tutankhamun, in honor to the Egyptian god Amun.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] His infant daughters represent the final genetically related generation of the Eighteenth Dynasty.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The last two members of the Eighteenth Dynasty—Ay and Horemheb—became rulers from the ranks of officials in the royal court, although Ay might also have been the maternal uncle of Akhenaten as a fellow descendant of Yuya and Tjuyu.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Ay may have married the widowed Great Royal Wife and presumed half-sister of Tutankhamun, Ankhesenamun, in order to obtain power; she did not live long afterward, with Ay instead ascending to the throne with his long-time wife Tey, who was originally Nefertiti's wet-nurse.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] His successor was Horemheb, a general who appeared to have been Tutankhamun's heir presumptive, and whose wife Mutnedjmet might have been sister of the former queen Nefertiti.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] It is possible that Horemheb took throne away from Ay in a coup d'état.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Although Ay's son or stepson Nakhtmin was named as his father/stepfather's Crown Prince, Nakhtmin seems to have died during the reign of Ay, leaving the opportunity for Horemheb to claim the throne next.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Horemheb also died without surviving children, having appointed his vizier, Pa-ra-mes-su, as his heir.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] This vizier ascended the throne in 1292 BC as Ramesses I, and was the first pharaoh of the Nineteenth Dynasty.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] This example to the right depicts a man named Ay who achieved the exalted religious positions of Second Prophet of Amun and High Priest of Mut at Thebes.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] His career flourished during the reign of Tutankhamun, when the statue was made.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The cartouches of King Ay, Tutankhamun's successor appearing on the statue, were an attempt by an artisan to "update" the sculpture.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The Eighteenth Dynasty empire conquered all of Lower Nubia under Thutmose I.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] By the reign of Thutmose III, the Egyptians directly controlled Nubia to the Nile river, 4th cataract, with Egyptian influence / tributaries extending beyond this point.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The Egyptians referred to the area as Kush and it was administered by the Viceroy of Kush.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The 18th dynasty obtained Nubian gold, animal skins, ivory, ebony, cattle, and horses, which were of exceptional quality.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The Egyptians built temples throughout Nubia.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] One of the largest and most important temples was dedicated to Amun at Jebel Barkal in the city of Napata.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] This Temple of Amun was enlarged by later Egyptian and Nubian Pharaohs, such as Taharqa.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Radiocarbon dating suggests that Dynasty XVIII may have started a few years earlier than the conventional date of 1550 BC.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The radiocarbon date range for its beginning is 1570–1544 BC, the mean point of which is 1557 BC.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] A 1973 X-ray examination of southern king, Seqenenre Tao, by American Egyptologists, Kent Weeks and James E.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Harris identified cranial similarities between his cranio-facial complex along with other Nubian and Old Kingdom Giza Skulls.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] In their view, this was supportive of scholarly interpretations that Sequenre Tao and his family may have held Nubian ancestry.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Robins and Shute (1983) performed X-ray measurements on the physical proportions of Upper Egyptian rulers such as Thutmose III, Amenhotep III, Tutankhamun.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The authors reported that the limbs of the pharaohs, like those of other Ancient Egyptians, had "negroid characteristics", in that the distal segments were relatively long in comparison with the proximal segments.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] An exception was Ramesses II, who appears to have had short legs below the knees.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] James Harris and Fawzia Hussien (1991) conducted an X-ray survey on southern based 18th dynasty royal mummies and examined the mummified remains of Thutmose II.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The results of the study determined that the mummy of Thutmose II had a craniofacial trait measurement that was common among Nubian populations.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] A genetic study, published in 2020, revealed Tutankhamun had the haplogroups YDNA R1b, which originated in western Asia and which today makes up 50–60% of the genetic pool of modern Europeans, and mtDNA K, which originated in the Near East.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] He shares this Y-haplogroup with his father, the KV55 mummy (Akhenaten), and grandfather, Amenhotep III (and his entire male ancestral line), and his mtDNA haplogroup with his mother, The Younger Lady, his grandmother, Tiye, and his great-grandmother, Thuya (and his entire female ancestral line).
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The profiles for Tutankhamun and Amenhotep III were incomplete, and the analysis produced differing probability figures despite having concordant allele results.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Because the relationships of these two mummies with the KV55 mummy had previously been confirmed in an earlier study, the haplogroup prediction of both mummies could be derived from the full profile of the KV55 data.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Keita analysed 8 Short Tandem loci (STR) data originally published by Hawass et al. in studies from 2010 and 2012.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The first of these studies had investigated familial relationships among 11 royal mummies of the New Kingdom, which included Tutankhamun and Amenhotep III, as well as potential inherited disorders and infectious diseases.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The second of these studies had investigated the Y-haplogroups and genetic kinship of Ramesses III and an unknown man buried along with him in the royal cache at Deir el Bahari.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Keita analysed the STR data from these studies using an algorithm that only has three choices: Eurasians, sub-Saharan Africans, and East Asians.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Using these three options, Keita concluded that the majority of the samples had a population "affinity with 'sub-Saharan' Africans in one affinity analysis".
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] However, Keita cautioned that this does not mean that the royal mummies "lacked other affiliations", which he argued had been obscured in typological thinking.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Keita further added that different "data and algorithms might give different results", reflecting the complexity of biological heritage and the associated interpretation.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] According to historian William Stiebling and archaeologist Susan N.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Helft, (2023) conflicting DNA analysis on recent genetic samples such as the Amarna royal mummies has led to a lack of consensus on the genetic makeup of the ancient Egyptians and their geographic origins.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] In 2025, biochemist Jean-Philippe Gourdine reviewed genetic data on the Ancient Egyptian populations in the international scholarly publication, General History of Africa Volume IX.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] In 2025, Christopher Ehret, David Schoenbrun, Steven A Brandt and Shomarka Keita issued a multidisciplinary review, noting the R1b M89 haplogroup subtype identified among the three Amarna pharaohs (Tutankhamun, Amenhotep III and Akhenaten) was not further specified.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The authors also stated that the R1b haplogroup usually interpreted as indicating a back migration to Africa from or via the Near East could have been attributed to Asian back migration or trans-Saharan connections as the genetic marker is found at relative high frequencies among Chadic populations.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Referencing a Short Tandem Report (STR) autosomal background analysis on the Amarna royal mummies, performed by Keita in an earlier publication, the authors considered this analysis could suggest closer trans-Saharan connections.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Ehret et al also disclosed through personal communication with the Gad team that "other eighteenth dynasty lineages in the Amarna period were found to be E1b1a (Gad et al 2020)".
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The authors further postulated that association of the palaeolithic Asian lineage (R1B) and an affiliation that is tropical African (E1b1a) is an example of admixture found in some Nile Valley populations, and that a mixture of lineages could illustrate Egypt being near a crossroads.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The pharaohs of the 18th Dynasty ruled for approximately 250 years (c.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The dates and names in the table are taken from Dodson and Hilton.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Many of the pharaohs were buried in the Valley of the Kings in Thebes (designated KV).
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] More information can be found on the Theban Mapping Project website.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Several diplomatic marriages are known for the New Kingdom.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] These daughters of foreign kings are often only mentioned in cuneiform texts and are not known from other sources.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The marriages were likely to have been a way to confirm good relations between these states.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Royal brother-sister marriages were observed, as a means to strengthen the royalty by echoing the practices in their creation myths.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] The Eighteenth Dynasty is well-recorded across Egyptian king lists, mostly due to being written extensively by their Nineteenth Dynasty successors.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] A Theban tomb, TT19, also provides a king list.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] It's possible the Turin King List originally listed the Eighteenth Dynasty, but it's now in a fragmentary state and some information is lost, including a section that contained Dynasties 18–19/20.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Manetho's now-lost work *Aegyptiaca* also provided individual reign lengths, however the lengths seem to be inaccurate since his sources were likely already corrupted due to the *damnatio memoriae* imposed over the Amarna rulers, and co-regency may have caused additional confusion.
[src:africa/18th-dynasty] Later Epitomes of the work were then misunderstood by various writers who conflated multiple kings into a single figure, failed to understand the number of kings in this dynasty.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] A widespread famine affected Ethiopia from 1983 to 1985.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The worst famine to hit the country in a century, it affected 7.75 million people (out of Ethiopia's 38–40 million) and left approximately 300,000 to 1.2 million dead.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] 2.5 million people were internally displaced whereas 400,000 refugees left Ethiopia.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] According to Human Rights Watch, more than half its mortality could be attributed to "human rights abuses causing the famine to come earlier, strike harder and extend further than would otherwise have been the case".
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] According to the United States Agency for International Development, "in the fall of 1984, the hardest hit regions were Tigray, Wollo, and Eritrea – areas with extremely limited road and transportation networks.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Moreover, these regions were the scenes of longstanding anti-government rebellions which created precarious security situations." Other areas of Ethiopia experienced famine for similar reasons, resulting in tens of thousands of additional deaths.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The famine as a whole took place a decade into the Ethiopian Civil War.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Since 1991, the favoured explanation for the famine of 1983–1985 is "war and drought".
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Throughout the feudal era, famines were common in Ethiopia, especially in the north.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Local famines were also frequent but also unrecorded.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The most infamous was the "Great Ethiopian Famine" which killed approximately one third of Ethiopia's population between 1888 and 1892.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In 1973, drought and feudal extractions caused a famine that killed 40,000 to 200,000 people in Wollo, resulting in protests in the capital of Addis Ababa, with Amhara youth decrying the seemingly ignored famine.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Despite attempts to suppress news of this famine, leaked reports contributed to the undermining of the government's legitimacy and served as a rallying point for dissidents, who complained that the wealthy classes and the Ethiopian government had ignored both the famine and the people who had died.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Then in 1974, a group of military officers known as the Derg overthrew Haile Selassie.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The Derg addressed the Wollo famine by creating the Relief and Rehabilitation Commission (RRC) to examine the causes of the famine and prevent its recurrence, and then abolishing feudal tenure in March 1975.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The RRC initially enjoyed more independence from the Derg than any other ministry, largely due to its close ties to foreign donors and the quality of some of its senior staff.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] As a result, insurgencies began to spread into the country's administrative regions.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] By late 1976 insurgencies existed in all of the country's fourteen administrative regions.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The Red Terror (1976–1978) marked the beginning of a steady deterioration in the economic state of the nation, coupled with extractive policies targeting rural areas.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The reforms of 1975 were revoked and the Agricultural Marketing Corporation (AMC) was tasked with extracting food from rural peasantry at low rates to placate the urban populations.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The very low fixed price of grain served as a disincentive to production, and some peasants had to buy grain on the open market in order to meet their AMC quota.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Citizens in Wollo, which continued to be stricken with drought, were required to provide a "famine relief tax" to the AMC until 1984.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The Derg also imposed a system of travel permits to restrict peasants from engaging in non-agricultural activities, such as petty trading and migrant labor, a major form of income supplementation.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] However, the collapse of the system of State Farms, a large employer of seasonal laborers, resulted in an estimated 500,000 farmers in northern Ethiopia losing a component of their income.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Grain wholesaling was declared illegal in much of the country, resulting in the number of grain dealers falling from between 20,000 and 30,000 to 4,942 in the decade after the revolution.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The nature of the RRC changed as the government became increasingly authoritarian.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Immediately after its creation, its experienced core of technocrats produced highly regarded analyses of Ethiopian famine and ably carried out famine relief efforts.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] However, by the 1980s, the Derg had compromised its mission.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The RRC began with the innocuous scheme of creating village workforces from the unemployed in state farms, and government agricultural schemes but, as the counter-insurgency intensified, the RRC was given responsibility for a program of forced resettlement and villagization.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] As the go-between for international aid organizations and foreign donor governments, the RRC redirected food to government militias, in particular in Eritrea and Tigray.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] It also encouraged international agencies to set up relief programs in regions with surplus grain production, which allowed the AMC to collect the excess food.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Finally, the RRC carried out a disinformation campaign during the 1980s famine, in which it portrayed the famine as being solely the result of drought and overpopulation and tried to deny the existence of the armed conflict that was occurring precisely in the famine-affected regions.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The RRC also claimed that the aid being given by it and its international agency partners were reaching all of the famine victims.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Due to organized government policies that deliberately multiplied the effects of the famine, around 1.2 million people died in Ethiopia from the famine where the majority of the death tolls were from the present day Tigray Region and Amhara Region and other parts of northern Ethiopia.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Before the 1983–1985 famine, two decades of wars of national liberation and other anti-government conflict had raged throughout northern Ethiopia and present-day Eritrea.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The most prominent feature of the fighting was the use of indiscriminate violence against civilians by the Ethiopian Army and Air Force.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Excluding those killed by famine and resettlement, more than 150,000 people were killed.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The economy of Ethiopia is based on agriculture: almost half of GDP, 60% of exports, and 80% of total employment come from agriculture.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Four Ethiopian provinces — Gojjam, Hararghe, Tigray and Wollo — all received record low rainfalls in the mid-1980s.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In the south, a separate and simultaneous cause was the government's response to Oromo Liberation Front (OLF) insurgency.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In 1984, Mengistu Haile Mariam announced that 46% of the Ethiopian Gross National Product would be allocated to military spending, creating the largest standing army in sub-Saharan Africa; the allocation for health in the government budget fell from 6% in 1973–1974 to 3% by 1990–1991.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Although a UN estimate of one million deaths is often quoted for the 1983–1985 famine, this figure has been challenged by famine scholar Alex de Waal.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In a major study, de Waal criticized the United Nations for being "remarkably cavalier" about the numbers of people who died, with the UN's one-million figure having "absolutely no scientific basis whatsoever," a fact which represents "a trivialization and dehumanization of human misery".
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] De Waal estimates that 400,000 to 500,000 died in the famine.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Nevertheless, the magnitude of the disaster has been well documented: in addition to hundreds of thousands of deaths, millions were made destitute.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Media activity in the West, along with the size of the crisis, led to the "Do They Know It's Christmas?" charity single and the July 1985 concert Live Aid, which elevated the international profile of the famine and helped secure international aid.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In the early to mid-1980s there were famines in two distinct regions of the country, resulting in several studies of one famine that try to extrapolate to the other or less cautious writers referring to a single widespread famine.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The famine in the southeast of the country was brought about by the Derg's counterinsurgency efforts against the OLF.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] However, most media referring to "the Ethiopian famine" of the 1980s refers to the severe famine in 1983–85 centered on Tigray and northern Wollo, which further affected Eritrea, Begemder and northern Shewa.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Living standards had been declining in these government-held regions since 1977, a "direct consequence" of the Derg's agricultural policies.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] A further major contributing factor to the famine were the Ethiopian government's enforced resettlement programs, utilized as part of its counter-insurgency campaign.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Despite RRC claims to have predicted the famine, there was little data as late as early 1984 indicating an unusually severe food shortage.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Following two major droughts in the late 1970s, 1980 and 1981 were rated by the RRC as "normal" and "above normal".
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The 1982 harvest was the largest ever, with the exception of central and eastern Tigray.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] RRC estimates for people "at-risk" of famine rose to 3.9 million in 1983 from 2.8 million in 1982, which was less than the 1981 estimate of 4.5 million.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In February and March 1983, the first signs of famine were recognized as poverty-stricken farmers began to appear at feeding centers, prompting international aid agencies to appeal for aid and the RRC to revise its famine assessment.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The harvest after the main (*meher*) harvest in 1983 was the third largest on record, with the only serious shortfall again being recorded in Tigray.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In response, grain prices in the two northern regions of Begemder and Gojjam fell.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The RRC claimed in May 1984 that the failure of the short rains (*belg*) constituted a catastrophic drought while neglecting to state that the *belg* crops form a fourth of crop yields where the *belg* falls, but none at all in the majority of Tigray.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] A quantitative measure of the famine are grain prices, which show high prices in eastern and central Tigray, spreading outward after the 1984 crop failure.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] A major drain on Ethiopia's economy was the ongoing civil war, which pitched rebel movements against the Soviet and Cuban-backed Derg government.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] This crippled the country's economy further and contributed to the government's lack of ability to handle the crisis to come.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] By mid-1984, it was evident that another drought and resulting famine of major proportions had begun to affect large parts of northern Ethiopia.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Just as evident was the government's inability to provide relief.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The almost total failure of crops in the north was compounded by fighting in and around Eritrea, which hindered the passage of relief supplies.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Although international relief organizations made a major effort to provide food to the affected areas, the persistence of drought and poor security conditions in the north resulted in continuing need as well as hazards for famine relief workers.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In late 1985, another year of drought was forecast, and by early 1986 the famine had spread to parts of the southern highlands, with an estimated 5.8 million people dependent on relief food.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In 1986, locust plagues exacerbated the problem.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Despite the fact that the government had access to only a minority of the famine-stricken population in the north, the great majority of the relief was channeled through the government side, prolonging the war.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The Ethiopian government's unwillingness to deal with the famine provoked universal condemnation by the international community.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Even many supporters of the Ethiopian regime opposed its policy of withholding food shipments to rebel areas.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The combined effects of famine and internal war had by then put the nation's economy into a state of decline.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The primary government response to the drought and famine was the decision to uproot large numbers of peasants who lived in the affected areas in the north and to resettle them in the west and southern part of the country.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In 1985 and 1986, about 600,000 people were moved, many forcibly, from their home villages and farms by the military and transported to various regions in the south.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Many peasants fled rather than allow themselves to be resettled; many of those who were resettled sought later to return to their native regions.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Several human rights organizations claimed that tens of thousands of peasants died as a result of forced resettlement.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] According to Human Rights Watch, at least 50,000 people died.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Another government plan involved villagization, which was a response not only to the famine but also to the poor security situation.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Beginning in 1985, peasants were forced to move their homesteads into planned villages, which were clustered around water, schools, medical services, and utility supply points to facilitate the distribution of those services.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Many peasants fled rather than acquiesce in relocation, which in general proved highly unpopular.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Additionally, the government in most cases failed to provide the promised services.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Far from benefiting agricultural productivity, the program caused a decline in food production.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Although temporarily suspended in 1986, villagization was subsequently resumed.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Close to 8 million people became famine victims during the drought of 1984, and over 1 million died.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In the same year (23 October), a BBC news crew was the first to document the famine, with Michael Buerk describing "a biblical famine in the 20th century" and "the closest thing to hell on Earth".
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The report shocked Britain, motivating its citizens to inundate relief agencies, such as Save the Children, with donations, and also to bring the world's attention to the crisis in Ethiopia.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In November 1984, the British Royal Air Force carried out the first airdrops from C-130 Hercules delivering food to the starving people.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Other countries including Sweden, East and West Germany, Poland, Canada, United States, the Soviet Union and Yugoslavia were also involved in the international response.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Buerk's news piece on the BBC was seen by Irish singer Bob Geldof, who quickly organised the charity supergroup Band Aid, primarily made up of the biggest British and Irish artists of the era.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Their single, "Do They Know It's Christmas?", was released on 3 December 1984 and became Britain's best-selling single within a few weeks, eventually selling 3.69 million copies domestically.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] It raised £8 million for famine relief within twelve months of its release.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Other charity singles soon followed; released in March 1985, "We Are the World" by USA for Africa was the most successful of these, selling 20 million copies worldwide.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Live Aid, a 1985 fund-raising effort headed by Geldof, induced millions of people in the West to donate money and to urge their governments to participate in the relief effort in Ethiopia.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Some of the proceeds also went to the famine hit areas of Eritrea.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In France, supergroup Chanteurs sans frontières released "SOS Éthiopie", which sold 1 million copies and raised 10 million francs (about 1.2 million dollars).
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In Canada, supergroup Northern Lights, consisting of Bryan Adams, The Guess Who, Rush, Anne Murray, John Candy, Neil Young, and among others sang "Tears Are Not Enough", which was produced by David Foster.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In Yugoslavia, supergroup YU Rock Misija recorded the charity single "Za milion godina" and organized a corresponding charity concert, raising a total of US$426,000.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Other charity initiatives raised money for Ethiopia.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] On 27 January 1985, members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints participated in a special fast, where members went without food for two meals and donated the money they would have used to buy food.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The fast raised $6 million for the famine victims in Ethiopia.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The manner in which international aid was routed through the RRC gave rise to criticism that forever changed the way in which governments and NGOs respond to international emergencies taking place within conflict situations.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] International aid supplied to the government and to relief agencies working alongside the government became part of the counter-insurgency strategy of the government.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] It, therefore, met a real and immediate need but also prolonged the life of Mengistu's government.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The response to the emergency raised disturbing questions about the relationship between humanitarian agencies and host governments.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] However, according to Peter Gill, in his 2010 book *Foreigners and Famine: Ethiopia Since Live Aid*, 7.9 million people faced starvation in 1984, resulting in over 600,000 deaths; while in 2003 13.2 million "faced the prospect of a famine and only 300 died".
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] On 3 March 2010, Martin Plaut of the BBC published evidence that millions of dollars' worth of aid to the Ethiopian famine were spent in buying weapons by the Tigrayan People's Liberation Front, a communist group trying to overthrow the Ethiopian communist government at the time.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Rebel soldiers said they posed as merchants as "a trick for the NGOs".
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The report also cited a CIA document saying aid was "almost certainly being diverted for military purposes".
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] One rebel leader estimated $95 million (£63 million).
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Plaut also said that other NGOs were under the influence or control of the Derg military junta.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Some journalists suggested that the Derg was able to use Live Aid and Oxfam money to fund its enforced resettlement and villagization programs, under which at least 3 million people are said to have been displaced and between 50,000 and 100,000 killed.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The United States Agency for International Development which provided foreign assistance during the famine, estimated that "more than 300,000" died.
[src:africa/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Other insider estimates put the total death toll in Ethiopia at "1.2 million dead, 400,000 refugees outside the country, 2.5 million people internally displaced, and almost 200,000 orphans".
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] The **2002 Morocco Cup** was a three-team cricket tournament which took place in Tangier, Morocco during August 2002.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] The tournament was the first occasion on which the highest level of international cricket had been played in North Africa.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] Pakistan, South Africa and Sri Lanka competed in the competition, which was funded by Abdul Rahman Bukhatir, a wealthy business man from the United Arab Emirates.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] Sri Lanka beat South Africa in the final to scoop the $250,000 prize money.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] The tournament, in addition to attracting TV audiences to Bukhatir's TEN Sports channel, promoted cricket in North Africa.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] All of the matches were played at the National Cricket Stadium in Tangier, a purpose built ground which cost $4 million, most of which was spent on the grandstand.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] The organisers of the competition were so keen to avoid any accusations of match-fixing that they installed closed-circuit television (CCTV) cameras in the team dressing rooms.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] During the group stage, Pakistan won only once; beating Sri Lanka in the second match of the tournament.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] Sri Lanka beat Pakistan in their other match, and defeated South Africa in both the side's group contests to finish top of the table.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] South Africa won both their matches against Pakistan to qualify for the final.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] In the final, Sri Lanka beat South Africa by 27 runs, led by a run-a-ball score of 71 from their captain Sanath Jayasuriya, and two wickets from each of Chaminda Vaas, Pulasthi Gunaratne and Muttiah Muralitharan.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] Jayasuriya finished the tournament as the leading run-scorer, aggregating 299 runs from his five appearances at an average of 59.80.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] Each of the top-three run-scorers were Sri Lankan; the highest Pakistani batsman was Mohammad Yousuf whose 153 runs placed him fourth, while South African Jacques Kallis was fifth with 141 runs.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] In contrast, Waqar Younis of Pakistan took the most wickets, 11, followed by a pair of South Africans – Allan Donald and Lance Klusener, who took 10 and 9 respectively.
[src:africa/2002-morocco-cup] Upul Chandana and Pulasthi Gunaratne were the leading Sri Lankans, claiming 8 wickets apiece.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The **2003 ICC Cricket World Cup** was the eighth Cricket World Cup, organised by the International Cricket Council (ICC).
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] It was co-hosted by South Africa, Zimbabwe and Kenya from 9 February to 23 March 2003.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] This edition of the World Cup was the first to be played in Africa.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The tournament featured 14 teams, the largest number in the World Cup's history at the time, playing a total of 54 matches.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] It followed the format introduced in the 1999 Cricket World Cup, with the teams divided into two groups, and the top three in each group qualifying for the Super Sixes stage.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The tournament saw numerous upsets, with host South Africa, Pakistan, West Indies and England all being eliminated at the group stage (South Africa missed by 1 run after misreading the Duckworth-Lewis method rules).
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] England forfeited their match with Zimbabwe, due to the political unrest in the country, which ultimately enabled Zimbabwe to reach the Super Sixes.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Similarly, New Zealand forfeited their match with Kenya, due to security reasons which enabled the latter to reach the semi-finals, the only non-Test playing nation to do so.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Another shock wave came two days after the tournament had started, when Shane Warne, at the time one of the game's leading spinners, was sent home in disgrace after testing positive for a banned substance.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was eventually won by Australia who won all 11 of their matches, beating India in the final played at the Wanderers Stadium in Johannesburg.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] This was also Australia's third World Cup win, the only team to do so.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Pakistani player Shoaib Akhtar also set a world record, becoming the fastest bowler in the history of cricket, delivering a record top speed of 161.3 km/h (100.23 mph) in a pool match against England.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Fourteen teams played in the 2003 World Cup, the largest number of teams to play in a Cricket World Cup at the time.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The 10 Test playing nations automatically qualified for the tournament including the recently appointed member Bangladesh, while Kenya also qualified automatically due to their full One Day International status.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The other three spots were filled by the top three teams in the 2001 ICC Trophy in Canada, which served as a qualifying tournament.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] These teams were, respectively, the Netherlands who won the ICC Trophy, Canada and Namibia.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] This was Namibia's World Cup debut, while the Netherlands and Canada were both appearing in the tournament for the second time, having previously appeared in 1996 and 1979 respectively.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The format used in the 1999 World Cup was retained, with the 14 teams divided into two groups of seven, and the top three from each group qualifying for the Super Sixes stage, carrying forward the results they had achieved against other qualifiers from their group.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The top four teams in the Super Sixes qualified for the semi-finals, and the winners of those matches contested the final.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The opening ceremony was held on 8 February 2003 at Newlands Cricket Ground, Cape Town and was attended by around 25,000 fans.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] South African President Thabo Mbeki officially declared the tournament open.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Tumi Makgabo served as the official master of ceremonies.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Marc Lottering, Johnny Clegg, Hugh Masekela and Nothembi Mkhwebane were main performers at the ceremony.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Six match referees and 19 umpires were selected to stand in the tournament.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The top three teams from each pool qualify for the next stage, carrying forward the points already scored against fellow qualifiers, plus a quarter of the points scored against the teams that failed to qualify.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Teams who qualified for the Super Six stage only played against the teams from the other group; results against the other teams from the same group were carried forward to this stage.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Teams that advanced to the semi-finals are highlighted in green.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] On a difficult, slow pitch at Port Elizabeth, Australia struggled their way to 212/7 against tight Sri Lankan bowling, thanks mainly to a great innings from Andrew Symonds (91* from 118 balls, 7 fours, 1 six), demonstrating again captain Ricky Ponting's faith in him.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Chaminda Vaas, continuing his excellent tournament, took three wickets.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Australia's pace attack then ripped through the Sri Lankan top order, with Brett Lee (3/35 in 8 overs) taking three early wickets and Glenn McGrath (1/20 in 7 overs) taking one.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] By the time rain arrived in the 39th over, continued tight bowling had squeezed Sri Lanka to 123/7, well behind the target given by the Duckworth–Lewis method.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] This is the match in which Adam Gilchrist famously "walked" despite being given not out.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The fairytale ended for the Kenyan team, the only non-Test-playing nation to ever make a World Cup semi-final.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Sachin Tendulkar (83 from 101 balls, 5 fours, 1 six) and Sourav Ganguly (111 from 114 balls, 5 fours, 5 sixes), batted the Kenyans out of the game as India reached a total of 270/4.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Under the Durban lights, the potent Indian seam attack of Zaheer Khan (3/14 in 9.2 overs), the experienced Javagal Srinath (1/11 in 7 overs) and Ashish Nehra (2/11 in 5 overs) ripped through the Kenyan top order.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Kenya were bowled out for 179, with only Steve Tikolo (56 from 83 balls, 5 fours, 2 sixes) putting up any significant resistance.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] India won the toss, and Ganguly, elected to field, hoping to take advantage of a pitch left damp by dew and rain.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] On a lively Wanderers Stadium pitch, the Australian openers took advantage of very wayward Indian opening bowlers to get off to a flying start.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Adam Gilchrist (57 from 48 balls, 8 fours, 1 six) and Matthew Hayden (37 from 54 balls, 5 fours) shared an opening partnership of 105 runs in 14 overs, forcing Ganguly to bring on the spinners unusually early.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The change of pace brought wickets with Adam Gilchrist, who had been swinging at everything, holing out off a sweep shot from the bowling of Harbhajan Singh.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Ponting and Martyn started efficiently, putting away bad balls but mostly keeping the scoring going with good running, then letting loose in the last ten overs, taking 109 from them.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Ponting in particular dispatched the bowling over the fence with fearsome regularity in scoring 8 sixes, the most from one batsman in any World Cup match at the time.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The final Australian total of 359 (2 wickets, 50 overs), at a run rate of 7.18 runs an over, was their then highest ever in ODI history.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] India's run chase was made even more difficult after their best batsman, Sachin Tendulkar, was out in the first over after skying a pull shot, Glenn McGrath completing the caught and bowled.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Nevertheless, Virender Sehwag's (82 from 81 balls, 10 fours, 3 sixes) run-a-ball half century gave India respectability as they maintained a high scoring rate.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Their only realistic hope—a washout—looked a possibility as the game was interrupted by rain with India at 3/103 after 17 overs.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] However, this rain passed by, and India's hopes were dashed when Sehwag was run out by Darren Lehmann, and again when Rahul Dravid (47 from 57 balls, 2 fours) was bowled by Andy Bichel, ending their partnership of 88 runs in 13.2 overs.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The security and political situation in Zimbabwe, and the appropriateness of playing there given the misdeeds of the regime of Robert Mugabe was a point of concern before the tournament.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Two Zimbabwean players, Andy Flower and Henry Olonga wore black armbands in their opening game protesting against the undemocratic rule in Zimbabwe.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Both men subsequently retired from Zimbabwean cricket, and began playing overseas.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] England faced a great deal of domestic pressure to boycott their match in Zimbabwe on political grounds and did not play, citing fears for the players' safety.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The boycott proved costly, as Zimbabwe advanced to the Super Sixes, just 2 points ahead of England, their total including the 4 points achieved from the walkover.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Similarly, New Zealand decided against playing in Kenya because of security fears which would ultimately cost them a semi-final spot.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] Australian star player Shane Warne was sent home from the cup the day before his team's opening game, after a positive drug test in a lead-up competition in Australia revealed that he had taken a banned diuretic.
[src:africa/2003-cricket-world-cup] The leg spinner claimed that he had taken a 'fluid pill' on the advice of his mother.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Africa straddles the equator and the prime meridian.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The continent is surrounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Arabian plate and the Gulf of Aqaba to the northeast, the Indian Ocean to the southeast and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:africa/africa-p01] France, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and Yemen have parts of their territories located on African geographical soil, mostly in the form of islands.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The continent includes Madagascar and various archipelagos.
[src:africa/africa-p01] It contains 54 fully recognised sovereign states, eight cities and islands that are part of non-African states, and two *de facto* independent states with limited or no recognition.
[src:africa/africa-p01] This count does not include Malta and Sicily, which are geologically part of the African continent.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, and Nigeria is its largest by population.
[src:africa/africa-p01] African nations cooperate through the establishment of the African Union, which is headquartered in Addis Ababa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Africa is highly biodiverse; it is the continent with the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:africa/africa-p01] However, Africa is also heavily affected by a wide range of environmental issues, including desertification, deforestation, water scarcity, and pollution.
[src:africa/africa-p01] These entrenched environmental concerns are expected to worsen as climate change impacts Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has identified Africa as the continent most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The history of Africa is long, complex, and varied, and has often been under-appreciated by the global historical community.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In African societies the oral word is revered, and they have generally recorded their history via oral tradition, which has led anthropologists to term them "oral civilisations", contrasted with "literate civilisations" which pride the written word.
[src:africa/africa-p01] African culture is rich and diverse both within and between the continent's regions, encompassing art, cuisine, music and dance, religion, and dress.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Africa, particularly Eastern Africa, is widely accepted to be the place of origin of humans and the Hominidae clade, also known as the great apes.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The earliest hominids and their ancestors have been dated to around 7 million years ago, and *Homo sapiens* (modern human) are believed to have originated in Africa 350,000 to 260,000 years ago.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Throughout history the continent saw the rise and fall of many kingdoms and empires, such as Ancient Egypt, Makuria, the Fatimids, Mali, the Asante, Kongo, the Luba, Bunyoro, Great Zimbabwe, Imerina, and the Zulu.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Despite the predominance of states, many societies were heterarchical and stateless.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Slave trades created various diasporas, especially in the Americas.
[src:africa/africa-p01] From the late-19th century to early 20th century, driven by the Second Industrial Revolution, most of Africa was rapidly conquered and colonised by European nations, save for Ethiopia and Liberia.
[src:africa/africa-p01] European rule had significant impacts on Africa's societies, and colonies were maintained for the purpose of economic exploitation and extraction of natural resources.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Most present states emerged from a process of decolonisation following World War II, and established the Organisation of African Unity in 1963, the predecessor to the African Union.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The nascent countries decided to keep their colonial borders, with traditional power structures used in governance to varying degrees.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Under Roman rule, Carthage became the capital of the province then named *Africa Proconsularis*, following the Roman victory over the Carthaginians in the Third Punic War in 146 BC, which also included the coastal part of modern Libya.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Latin suffix *-ica* can sometimes be used to denote a land (e.g., in *Celtica* from *Celtae*, as used by Julius Caesar).
[src:africa/africa-p01] The later Muslim region of Ifriqiya, following its conquest of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire's *Exarchatus Africae*, also preserved a form of the name.
[src:africa/africa-p01] According to the Romans, Africa lies to the west of Egypt, while "Asia" was used to refer to Anatolia and lands to the east.
[src:africa/africa-p01] A definite line was drawn between the two continents by the geographer Ptolemy (85–165 CE), indicating Alexandria along the Prime Meridian and making the isthmus of Suez and the Red Sea the boundary between Asia and Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] As Europeans came to understand the real extent of the continent, the idea of "Africa" expanded with their knowledge.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In accordance with African cosmology, African historical consciousness viewed historical change and continuity, order and purpose within the framework of man and his environment, the gods, and his ancestors, and he believed himself part of a holistic spiritual entity.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In African societies, the historical process is largely a communal one, with eyewitness accounts, hearsay, reminiscences, and occasionally visions, dreams, and hallucinations crafted into narrative oral traditions which are performed and transmitted through generations.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In oral traditions time is sometimes mythical and social, and ancestors were considered historical actors.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Mind and memory shapes traditions, as events are condensed over time and crystallise into clichés.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Oral tradition can be exoteric or esoteric.
[src:africa/africa-p01] It speaks to people according to their understanding, unveiling itself in accordance with their aptitudes.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Africa is considered by most paleoanthropologists to be the oldest inhabited territory on Earth, with the Human species originating from the continent.
[src:africa/africa-p01] During the mid-20th century, anthropologists discovered many fossils and evidence of human occupation perhaps as early as seven million years ago ("Before Present"; BP).
[src:africa/africa-p01] Fossil remains of several species of early apelike humans thought to have evolved into modern humans, such as *Australopithecus afarensis* radiometrically dated to approximately 3.9–3.0 million years BP, *Paranthropus boisei* (c.
[src:africa/africa-p01] 2.3–1.4 million years BP) and *Homo ergaster* (c.
[src:africa/africa-p01] 1.9 million–600,000 years BP) have been discovered.
[src:africa/africa-p01] After the evolution of *Homo sapiens* approximately 350,000 to 260,000 years BP in Africa, the continent was mainly populated by groups of hunter-gatherers.
[src:africa/africa-p01] These first modern humans left Africa and populated the rest of the globe during the Out of Africa II migration dated to approximately 50,000 years BP, exiting the continent either across Bab-el-Mandeb over the Red Sea, the Strait of Gibraltar in Morocco, or the Isthmus of Suez in Egypt.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Other migrations of modern humans within the African continent have been dated to that time, with evidence of early human settlement found in Southern Africa, Southeast Africa, North Africa, and the Sahara.
[src:africa/africa-p01] However, the warming and drying climate meant that by 5,000 BC, the Sahara region was becoming increasingly dry and hostile.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Around 3500 BC, due to a tilt in the Earth's orbit, the Sahara experienced a period of rapid desertification.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The domestication of cattle in Africa preceded agriculture and seems to have existed alongside hunter-gatherer cultures.
[src:africa/africa-p01] It is speculated that by 6,000 BC, cattle were domesticated in North Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In West Africa, a wet phase ushered in an expanding rainforest and wooded savanna from Senegal to Cameroon.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Between 9,000 and 5,000 BC, Niger–Congo speakers domesticated the oil palm and raffia palm.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Black-eyed peas and voandzeia (African groundnuts), were domesticated, followed by okra and kola nuts.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Since most of the plants grew in the forest, the Niger–Congo speakers invented polished stone axes for clearing forest.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Pygmies are thought to have inhabited Central Africa for many millennia, splitting into eastern and western groups around 5,000 BP.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Over 150,000 BP, there was an early dispersal of anatomically modern humans to Southern Africa, equated with the modern-day Khoisan who have preserved their traditional hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:africa/africa-p01] From 3500 BC, nomes (ruled by nomarchs) coalesced to form the kingdoms of Lower Egypt and Upper Egypt in northeast Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Around 3100 BC Upper Egypt conquered Lower Egypt to unify Egypt under the 1st dynasty, with the process of consolidation and assimilation completed by the time of the 3rd dynasty who formed the Old Kingdom of Egypt in 2686 BC.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Kingdom of Kerma emerged around this time to become the dominant force in Nubia, controlling territory as large as Egypt between the 1st and 4th cataracts of the Nile.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The height of the Old Kingdom saw the construction of many great pyramids, though under the 6th dynasty power gradually decentralised to the nomarchs, culminating in the disintegration of the kingdom, exacerbated by drought and famine.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Around 2055 BC, the 11th dynasty, based in Thebes, conquered the others to form the Middle Kingdom of Egypt, and the 12th dynasty expanded into Lower Nubia at the expense of Kerma.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Around 1700 BC, the Middle Kingdom fractured in two, and the Hyksos (a militaristic people from Palestine) invaded and conquered Lower Egypt, while Kerma coordinated invasions deep into Egypt to reach its greatest extent.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In 1550 BC, the 18th dynasty expelled the Hyksos, and established the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The New Kingdom conquered the Levant from the Canaanites, Mittani, Amorites, and Hittites, and extinguished Kerma, incorporating Nubia into the empire, and sending the Egyptian empire into its golden age.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Internal struggles, drought, famine, and invasions by a confederation of seafaring peoples contributed to the New Kingdom's collapse in 1069 BC.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The New Kingdom's collapse liberated the Kingdom of Kush in Nubia, which manoeuvred into power in Upper Egypt and conquered Lower Egypt in 754 BC to form the Kushite Empire.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Kushites ruled for a century and oversaw a revival in pyramid building, until they were driven out of Egypt by the Assyrians in 663 BC in reprisal for their expansion towards the Assyrian Empire.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Assyrians installed a puppet dynasty that later gained independence and once more unified Egypt, until it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire in 525 BC.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Egypt briefly regained independence from the Achaemenids under the 28th dynasty from 404 to 343 BC.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The conquest of Achaemenid Egypt by Alexander the Great in 332 BC marked the beginning of Hellenistic rule and the installation of the Macedonian Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Ptolemaics lost their holdings outside of Africa to the Seleucids in the Syrian Wars, expanded into Cyrenaica, and briefly occupied part of Kush in the 3rd century BC.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 1st century BC, Ptolemaic Egypt became entangled in a Roman civil war, leading to its conquest by the Romans in 30 BC.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Kush persisted as a major regional power until, having been weakened from internal rebellion amid worsening climatic conditions, invasions by Aksum and the Noba caused their disintegration into Makuria, Alodia, and Nobatia around the 5th century AD.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, there was the Land of Punt, a kingdom on the Red Sea which was a close trading partner of Ancient Egypt in the 3rd and 2nd millennia BC.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Rodolfo Fattovich equated it to the Gash Group in the Sudanese-Eritrean lowlands, and some scholars have hypothesised modern-day Somalia, while Kenneth Kitchen and Felix Chami locate it on Zanzibar Island.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the Eritrean-Ethiopian Highlands, the kingdom of dʿmt rose c.
[src:africa/africa-p01] 980 BC as the region was incorporated into global trading networks, and it exhibited Sabaean influences which most scholars attribute to a small migration of Sabaeans and their assimilation.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Several scholars consider there to have been other contemporaneous states, and dʿmt's collapse in the mid-1st century BC saw the region inhabited by small polities.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Modern-day Somalia was inhabited by nomadic pastoralists, and along the Horn's coast there were many ancient Somali city-states that thrived off of the wider Red Sea trade, and enjoyed a lucrative monopoly on cinnamon from Ancient India due to their freedom from Roman interference.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 1st century AD, the Kingdom of Aksum rose from a city-state to rule much of the northern Ethiopian-Eritrean Highlands and the Red Sea port of Adulis.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Aksum was described as one of the four great powers by Persian prophet Mani in the 3rd century.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Aksum's king converted from traditional religion to Christianity in the 4th century, gradually followed by the population.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 6th century, Aksum conquered South Arabia, though struggled to maintain control over it, and began to gradually lose its dominance over Red Sea trade to Persians and Arabs.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Northwest Africa (the Maghreb) was inhabited by Berber semi-nomadic pastoralists.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 1st millennium BC, Phoenician migration and settlement came in search for precious metals in the Gulf of Tunis.
[src:africa/africa-p01] This grew into Ancient Carthage after gaining independence from Phoenicia in the 6th century BC, and they built an extensive trading empire with a strict mercantile network.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Carthage's collapse and conquest by Rome in the Punic Wars (3rd and 2nd centuries BC) saw Numidia and Mauretania become major powers in the Maghreb.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 2nd century BC Mauretania fought alongside Numidia's Jugurtha against the Romans in the Jugurthine War after he had usurped the Numidian throne from a Roman ally.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Together they inflicted heavy casualties, with the war only ending inconclusively when Mauretania's Bocchus I sold out Jugurtha to the Romans.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, both came under direct Roman rule.
[src:africa/africa-p01] While traditional religion predominated among Berbers, some people converted to Christianity.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 5th century AD the Vandals conquered Roman Africa before the fall of Rome, though the province was reconquered by the Byzantines a century later.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Large swathes of indigenous peoples regained self-governance in Masuna and its numerous successor polities in the Maghreb, including the kingdoms of Ouarsenis, Aurès, and Altava.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the western Sahel the rise of settled communities occurred largely as a result of the domestication of millet and of sorghum, and cattle pastoralism began c.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Extensive east-west belts of deserts, grasslands, and forests from north to south were crucial for the moulding of their respective societies and meant that symbiotic trade relations developed in response to the differing environments.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Beginning around 4000 BC, the Tichitt culture in modern-day Mauritania and Mali is the oldest known complexly organised society in West Africa, while others included the Kintampo culture in modern-day Ghana, the Nok culture in modern-day Nigeria, and the Daima culture around Lake Chad.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 3rd century AD, a wet period in the Sahel created areas for human habitation and exploitation that had not been habitable for the best part of a millennium.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Ghana Empire (also called *Wagadu*) rose out of the Tichitt culture, growing wealthy following the introduction of the camel to the western Sahel, which revolutionised the trans-Saharan trade that linked their capital and Aoudaghost with Tahert and Sijilmasa in North Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Soninke tradition holds that the final founding of Wagadu occurred after Dinga did a deal with Bida, a serpent deity who was guarding a well, to sacrifice one maiden a year in exchange for assurance regarding plenty of rainfall and gold supply.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Based on large tumuli scattered across West Africa dating to this period, several scholars have speculated that there were further simultaneous and preceding states relative to Wagadu.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the Grasslands of northwestern Cameroon, Bantu-speaking agriculturalists started to gradually migrate south sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Despite intensive research, the cause of the migrations, and that of the directions taken, is still unclear, however there is consensus that there were multiple dispersal events.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Around 1500 BC, Bantu speakers reached central Cameroon.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The 'Western Stream' likely followed the coast and the major rivers of the Congo system southwards to reach the southern fringe of the Congolian Rainforest around 500 BC (some may have used the sea to circumvent the rainforest).
[src:africa/africa-p01] Their arrival coincided with the spread of iron metallurgy through Central Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Meanwhile, the 'Eastern Stream' travelled either the northern fringe of the rainforest or the Ubangi River eastwards, and reached just west of Lake Victoria around 500 BC.
[src:africa/africa-p01] While there, Bantu speakers adopted iron metallurgy from Cushitic speakers already present, and coexisted with them.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Dispersal from the Great Lakes region occurred in two more streams.
[src:africa/africa-p01] One went west to meet the Western Stream in the DR Congo and Angola, while the other went south and spread across Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, Bantu speakers reached central modern-day Tanzania and near Dar es Salaam, before rapidly moving southwards along the coast to reach modern-day Kwazulu Natal in South Africa around the 3rd century AD.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Throughout this, Bantu speakers displaced, replaced, or intermarried with and absorbed hunter-gatherer and agricultural groups.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 7th and 8th centuries, as part of the Arab conquests which sought to spread Islamic rule, the Rashidun and Umayyad caliphates conquered North Africa at the expense of the Byzantine Empire and Berber leaders such as Kusaila and Kahina.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Large numbers of Berber and Coptic people willingly converted to Islam, and followers of Abrahamic religions ('People of the Book') were protected, though followers of Berber traditional religion were violently oppressed.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 8th century the Berber Revolt rocked the Caliphate and Berber dynasties took control over the Maghreb, while the Tulunids briefly controlled Egypt.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 10th century, the Fatimids rose to power in modern-day Tunisia, established a rival caliphate, and conquered Egypt, before expanding into the Middle East.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 11th century the Almoravids conquered the Maghreb and intervened in the Christian reconquest of Iberia.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Saladin, a Fatimid vizier, usurped power in the 12th century and established the Ayyubid dynasty which restored Egyptian prestige, while the Almohad revolution deposed the Almoravids to the east.
[src:africa/africa-p01] After Christian gains in Iberia in the 13th century, the Almohads disintegrated into the Marinids, Zayyanids, and Hafsids in modern-day Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia respectively.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the face of Mongol expansion, Mamluk generals seized power in Egypt and expanded into the Middle East.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the early-16th century, the Ottoman Empire rapidly conquered North Africa (save for Morocco, now under Saadi rule) to counter Spanish expansionism.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the following centuries, over a million Europeans are estimated to have been captured and enslaved by Barbary corsairs.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Ottoman regencies became more independent during the 18th century.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the central Sahel around Lake Chad, the Kanem–Bornu Empire ruled from the 6th century, and projected power over the Hausa Kingdoms.
[src:africa/africa-p01] To the east during 7th century, Makuria conquered Nobatia to become the dominant power in the region and resisted Muslim expansion.
[src:africa/africa-p01] They later entered a severe decline following civil war and Arab migrations to the Sudan and had disintegrated by the 15th century, giving rise to the Funj Sultanate.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Tunjur empire's collapse in the central Sudan saw the rise of the Bagirmi, Wadai, and Darfur sultanates, which frequently raided the populations to their south for slaves.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, Aksum lost control of the Red Sea, and its isolation from Christendom caused Ethiopian society to introspect and take inspiration from the Old Testament.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Islamised Beja invaded the Ethiopian Highlands, forcing Aksum to migrate south, where, according to tradition, Aksum's expansion was met by a Jewish or traditionalist queen who destroyed the state c.
[src:africa/africa-p01] During the 13th century, hegemony in the Horn was contested by the Christian Zagwe, the Muslims of Shewa, and the traditionalist Damot; the Solomonic dynasty overthrew the Zagwe to found the Ethiopian Empire, while Shewa was replaced by Ifat.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Soon after, Ethiopia conquered Damot and the Muslim states, entering into a 'golden age'.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 16th century Muslims united behind Adal in *jihad* to reconquer the Muslim lands and occupy Ethiopia, until, with Portuguese assistance, Ethiopia counter-attacked and its sovereignty was restored in a reduced state.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries also saw Oromo invasions into the Horn, weakening Ethiopia further and causing the collapse of Adal, while Ajuran on the east coast also disintegrated.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Ethiopia briefly consolidated its authority in the late-17th century, though the turn of the century saw fragmentation and gradually-increasing anarchy, which continued throughout the 18th century.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the Sahel region of West Africa, the Ghana Empire formed from between the 2nd and 8th centuries, while from the 7th century the Gao Empire ruled to its east.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Almoravid capture of royal Aoudaghost led to Ghana's conversion to Islam in the 11th century, and climatic changes led to Ghana's conquest by its vassal Sosso in the 13th century.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Sosso was quickly overthrown by the Mali Empire who conquered Gao and dominated the trans-Saharan trade.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Mossi Kingdoms were established to its south.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The 15th century saw the crumbling of the Mali Empire, with the dominant power in the region becoming the Songhai Empire centered on Gao.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Weakened by internal conflict, in 1591 Gao was conquered by Morocco, and the political vacuum came to be filled by the Segou Empire and several other states.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The once lucrative trans-Saharan trade gradually lost its prominence to the coastal Atlantic trade with Europeans, and the following centuries saw many droughts, famines, and epidemics.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the forest regions of West Africa, various kingdoms and empires flourished, such as the Yoruba empires of Ife and Oyo, the Igbo Kingdom of Nri, the Edo Kingdom of Benin (famous for its art), the Dagomba Kingdom of Dagbon, and the Akan kingdoms of Bonoman and Adanse.
[src:africa/africa-p01] They came into contact with the Portuguese in the 15th century which saw the start of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Asante Empire was established in present-day Ghana.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Between 1515 and 1800, 8 million Africans were exported in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the western Congo Basin by the 13th century there were three main confederations of states: the Seven Kingdoms, Mpemba, and one led by Vungu.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 14th century the Kingdom of Kongo emerged and dominated the region, with the Tio Kingdom to its north and Mwene Muji to its northeast.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Over the course of the late-16th and 17th centuries, the Portuguese sought to conquer Ndongo (allied to Matamba) in the Angolan Wars; despite fierce resistance from Queen Nzinga, and brief occupation of Luanda by the Dutch (allied to Kongo), Portugal controlled most of Ndongo by the 1670s.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The late-17th century saw Kongo fragment between royal houses as several vassals broke away; by the time of Kongo's restoration in 1709, it had ceased being the dominant regional power.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Also during the 17th century, in the textile-producing northeast, the Boma, Yaka, and possibly the Kuba and Pende kingdoms broke away from Mwene Muji.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the eastern Congo Basin, farmers, fishermen, and hunters (often Pygmies) built symbiotic relations.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Jan Vansina wrote that in the southern savanna 'lords of the land' held priestly roles due to their special relationship with the spirits of the land, and held sway over multiple villages, effectively ruling embryonic kingdoms.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Accordingly, as lineages grew, authority was opportunistically absorbed or incorporated by force.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The centre of the Luba Empire is yet to undergo archaeological research, meaning knowledge about its rise is limited; its foundation is typically dated to the 14th/15th centuries, though scholarly estimates range from the 8th to 17th centuries.
[src:africa/africa-p01] A Lunda state formed in the Nkalany Valley (estimates range from c.
[src:africa/africa-p01] 1700), in the 18th century, Lunda rapidly expanded into an extensive commonwealth across the southern savanna, using the institutions of perpetual kinship and positional succession to incorporate peoples.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Meanwhile, Luba expanded its number of tributaries, in some cases using its widely acknowledged prestige to intervene in succession disputes and distribute ritually-powerful royal regalia related to *bulopwe* (sacred kingship), in other cases using conquest.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the northern Great Lakes, the Empire of Kitara rose around the 11th century, famed for its oral traditions.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Peter Robertshaw considered its rulers (the Chwezi) to have been religious leaders who utilised networks of hill-top shrines to project authority.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Around 1500, severe droughts and famine destabilised the region, occurring again during the early-17th and 18th centuries.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Luo-speaking peoples migrated from the Upper Nile basin into modern-day Uganda, and a Biito dynasty replaced the Chwezi in Bunyoro-Kitara.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Over the following centuries, the kingdoms of Bunyoro-Kitara, Buganda, and Rwanda struggled for hegemony among others.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Bunyoro raided states to the south such as Nkore and Rwanda.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Mpororo rose and fragmented during the 18th century, while Buganda rapidly expanded at the expense of Bunyoro to become the major power in the region.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The East African interior was inhabited by pastoralist Cushitic and Nilotic speakers, along with Bantu speakers who continued to expand and adapt to their lands while absorbing the former two; the 17th century saw the establishment of tributary systems that stabilised the region.
[src:africa/africa-p01] On the Swahili coast the Swahili city-states thrived off of the Indian Ocean trade and gradually Islamized, giving rise to the Kilwa Sultanate from the 10th century.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 15th century, trade routes for Zimbabwean gold shifted north, weakening Kilwa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Portuguese arrived at the coast soon after, and exploited divisions between coastal city-states to gain control over them while utilising a powerful navy.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the 17th and 18th centuries, Lamu-Swahili cities rebelled against the Portuguese and allied the Omani Empire which supplanted Portuguese rule.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Madagascar was settled by Austronesian peoples between the 5th and 7th centuries, as societies organized at the behest of *hasina* and competed over with one another over the island's estuaries and bridgeheads.
[src:africa/africa-p01] From around the 15th century, southern Madagascar became integrated into global trade; the Sakalava Empire rose to dominate west-coastal trade, accompanied by numerous other states, and the island saw several failed European colonial ventures.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In Southern Africa, an early kingdom was Mapungubwe, which collapsed c.
[src:africa/africa-p01] 1300 as Great Zimbabwe, with its monumental dry-stone walls, rose to become the region's main political and economic centre.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Following shifting trade routes north to the Zambezi and unclear circumstances, Great Zimbabwe entered into decline and was succeeded by the Mutapa Empire and Kingdom of Butua in the 15th century.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Mutapa was briefly vassalised by the Portuguese in the 17th century, the latter-half of which saw widespread famine and disease, until Changamire Dombo revolted in the 1680s, conquered Butua to found the Rozvi Empire, and expelled all Portuguese from the Zimbabwean Plateau.
[src:africa/africa-p01] North of the Zambezi, Maravi around Lake Malawi expanded in the 17th century, but the collapse of its succession system in the 18th century precipitated its disintegration.
[src:africa/africa-p01] By the late-1st millennium CE, Bantu-speaking farmers populated most of Southern Africa's cultivable savannas, reaching southwards to the Kei River; they traded goods such as livestock, grain, and metal tools between communities and with hunter-gatherers.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Further south, the Dutch began colonizing the western Cape in the 17th century, and Britain seized control of the colony around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the late-18th century, the interplay of pre-existing trends of political centralization with the effects of international trade, environmental instability, and European colonisation set the *Mfecane* ("Crushing") in motion, as various African states were founded.
[src:africa/africa-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, many of Africa's economic and political structures were unstable and brittle as a result of long-term effects of the slave trade.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In Egypt Muhammad Ali led a national movement to seize power from Ottoman suzerainty, instituting sweeping reforms and greatly strengthening Egyptian power by militaristic expansion.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Meanwhile, in West Africa the Fula *jihad*s, which had been gaining momentum throughout the 18th century, culminated in the establishment of the expansive Sokoto and Hamdullahi caliphates.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In the Horn, Ethiopia underwent reforms, seeking to revive the imperial state, something that was later achieved by Menelik II's conquests.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In Southern Africa the *Mfecane* propelled large long-distance migrations that caused widespread disruption across the vast region, while several Boer republics were founded.
[src:africa/africa-p01] European campaigns to abolish the Atlantic slave trade led to supply refocusing on internal markets and saw the rapid growth of the Indian Ocean slave trade.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Across the continent many rulers attempted reforms and indigenous forms of 'modernisation', however these efforts were consistently undermined by European traders and missionaries as the tide of European encroachment rose.
[src:africa/africa-p01] For 400 years, European nations had mainly limited their involvement to trading stations on the African coast, with few daring to venture inland.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Industrial Revolution in Europe produced several technological innovations which assisted them in overcoming this 400-year pattern.
[src:africa/africa-p01] One was the development of repeating rifles, which were easier and quicker to load than muskets.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Maxim developed the maxim gun, the model of the modern-day machine gun.
[src:africa/africa-p01] European states kept these weapons largely among themselves by refusing to sell these weapons to African leaders.
[src:africa/africa-p01] African germs took numerous European lives and deterred permanent settlements.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Diseases such as yellow fever, sleeping sickness, yaws, and leprosy made Africa a very inhospitable place for Europeans.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The deadliest disease was malaria, endemic throughout Tropical Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In 1854, the discovery of quinine and other medical innovations helped to make conquest and colonisation in Africa possible.
[src:africa/africa-p01] There were strong motives for the conquest of Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Raw materials were needed for European factories, and free trade was championed to prevent Africans from regulating their economies.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Prestige and imperial rivalries were at play.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Acquiring African colonies would show rivals that a nation was powerful and significant.
[src:africa/africa-p01] These contextual factors forged the Scramble for Africa; during the late-19th and early-20th centuries the European powers partitioned and conquered almost all of Africa despite fierce resistance (only Ethiopia and Liberia remained independent).
[src:africa/africa-p01] Traditional leaders were incorporated into the colonial regimes as a form of indirect rule to extract human and natural resources and curb organized resistance.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Colonial borders were drawn unilaterally by the Europeans, often cutting across bonds of kinship, language, culture, and established routes, and sometimes incorporating groups who previously had little in common.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The threat to trade routes was mitigated by poor policing and African entrepreneurs (viewed as smugglers) who exploited the differing tax and legal schemes.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The first few decades of European colonialism saw intense violence, disorder, and atrocities, such as that of the Congo Free State, German South West Africa, and French Algeria, with the late colonial period relatively peaceful in comparison.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Colonial rule had wide-reaching effects on African societies, such as the spread of Christianity as part of the 'civilising mission'.
[src:africa/africa-p01] African culture was strongly denigrated and persecuted, as pervasive racial discrimination deepened the scars of humiliation.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Imperial rule by Europeans continued until after the conclusion of World War II, when almost all remaining colonial territories gradually obtained formal independence.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Independence movements in Africa gained momentum following World War II, which left the major European powers weakened.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In 1951, Libya, a former Italian colony, gained independence.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In 1956, Tunisia and Morocco won their independence from France.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Ghana followed suit the next year (March 1957), becoming the first of the sub-Saharan colonies to be granted independence.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Over the next decade, waves of decolonisation took place across the continent, culminating in the 1960 Year of Africa and the establishment of the Organisation of African Unity in 1963.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Portugal's overseas presence in sub-Saharan Africa (most notably in Angola, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, and São Tomé and Príncipe) lasted from the 16th century to 1975, after the Estado Novo regime was overthrown in a military coup in Lisbon.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Rhodesia unilaterally declared independence from the United Kingdom in 1965, under the white minority government of Ian Smith, but was not internationally recognised as an independent state (as Zimbabwe) until 1980, when black nationalists gained power after a bitter guerrilla war.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Although South Africa was one of the first African countries to gain independence, the state remained under the control of the country's white minority, initially through qualified voting rights and from 1956 by a system of racial segregation known as apartheid, until 1994.
[src:africa/africa-p01] As of 2025, Africa contains 54 sovereign countries.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Since independence, African states have frequently been hampered by instability, corruption, violence, and authoritarianism.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The vast majority of African states are republics that operate under some form of the presidential system of rule.
[src:africa/africa-p01] However, few of them have been able to sustain democratic governments on a permanent basis—per the criteria laid out by Lührmann et al.
[src:africa/africa-p01] (2018), only Botswana and Mauritius have been consistently democratic for the entirety of their post-colonial history.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Most African countries have experienced several coups or periods of military dictatorship.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Between 1990 and 2018, though, the continent as a whole has trended towards more democratic governance.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Upon independence an overwhelming majority of Africans lived in extreme poverty.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The continent suffered from the lack of infrastructural or industrial development under colonial rule, along with political instability.
[src:africa/africa-p01] With limited financial resources or access to global markets, relatively stable countries such as Kenya still experienced only very slow economic development.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Only a handful of African countries succeeded in obtaining rapid economic growth prior to 1990.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Exceptions include Libya and Equatorial Guinea, both of which possess large oil reserves.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Instability throughout the continent after decolonisation resulted primarily from marginalisation of ethnic groups, and corruption.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Faced with increasingly frequent and severe violence, military rule was widely accepted by the population of many countries as means to maintain order, and during the 1970s and 1980s a majority of African countries were controlled by military dictatorships.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Territorial disputes between nations and rebellions by groups seeking independence were also common in independent African states.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The most devastating of these was the Nigerian Civil War, fought between government forces and an Igbo separatist republic, which resulted in a famine that killed 1–2 million people.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Two civil wars in Sudan, the first lasting from 1955 to 1972 and the second from 1983 to 2005, collectively killed around 3 million.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Both were fought primarily on ethnic and religious lines.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Cold War conflicts between the United States and the Soviet Union also contributed to instability.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Both the Soviet Union and the United States offered considerable incentives to African political and military leaders who aligned themselves with the superpowers' foreign policy.
[src:africa/africa-p01] As an example, during the Angolan Civil War, the Soviet and Cuban aligned MPLA and the American aligned UNITA received the vast majority of their military and political support from these countries.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Many African countries became highly dependent on foreign aid.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The sudden loss of both Soviet and American aid at the end of the Cold War and fall of the USSR resulted in severe economic and political turmoil in the countries most dependent on foreign support.
[src:africa/africa-p01] There was a major famine in Ethiopia between 1983 and 1985, killing up to 1.2 million people, which most historians attribute primarily to the forced relocation of farmworkers and seizure of grain by the communist Derg government, further exacerbated by the civil war.
[src:africa/africa-p01] In 1994 a genocide in Rwanda resulted in up to 800,000 deaths, added to a severe refugee crisis and fuelled the rise of militia groups in neighbouring countries.
[src:africa/africa-p01] This contributed to the outbreak of the first and second Congo Wars, which were the most devastating military conflicts in modern Africa, with up to 5.5 million deaths, making it by far the deadliest conflict in modern African history and one of the costliest wars in human history.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Various conflicts between various insurgent groups and governments continue.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Since 2003, there has been an ongoing conflict in Darfur (Sudan), which peaked in intensity from 2003 to 2005 with notable spikes in violence in 2007 and 2013–15, killing around 300,000 people total.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Boko Haram Insurgency primarily within Nigeria (with considerable fighting in Niger, Chad, and Cameroon as well) has killed around 350,000 people since 2009.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Most African conflicts have been reduced to low-intensity conflicts as of 2022.
[src:africa/africa-p01] However, the Tigray War from 2020 to 2022 killed an estimated 300,000–500,000 people, primarily due to famine.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Overall though, violence across Africa has greatly declined in the 21st century, with the end of civil wars in Angola, Sierra Leone, and Algeria in 2002, Liberia in 2003, and Sudan and Burundi in 2005.
[src:africa/africa-p01] The Second Congo War, which involved 9 countries and several insurgent groups, ended in 2003.
[src:africa/africa-p01] This decline in violence coincided with many countries abandoning communist-style command economies and opening up for market reforms, which over the course of the 1990s and 2000s promoted the establishment of permanent, peaceful trade between neighbouring countries (see Capitalist peace).
[src:africa/africa-p01] Improved stability and economic reforms have led to a great increase in foreign investment into many African nations, mainly from China, which further spurred economic growth.
[src:africa/africa-p01] Between 2000 and 2014, annual GDP growth in sub-Saharan Africa averaged 5.02%, doubling its total GDP from $811 billion to $1.63 trillion (constant 2015 USD).
[src:africa/africa-p01] North Africa experienced comparable growth rates.
[src:africa/africa-p01] A significant part of this growth can also be attributed to the facilitated diffusion of information technologies and specifically the mobile telephone.
[src:africa/africa-p01] While several individual countries have maintained high growth rates, since 2014 overall growth has considerably slowed, primarily as a result of falling commodity prices, continued lack of industrialisation, and epidemics such as Ebola and COVID-19.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa is the largest of the three great southward projections from the largest landmass of the Earth.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Separated from Europe by the Mediterranean Sea, it is joined to Asia at its northeast extremity by the Isthmus of Suez (transected by the Suez Canal), 163 km (101 mi) wide.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Geopolitically, Egypt's Sinai Peninsula east of the Suez Canal is often considered part of Africa as well.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The coastline is 26,000 km (16,000 mi) long, and the absence of deep indentations of the shore is illustrated by the fact that Europe, which covers only 10,400,000 km2 (4,000,000 sq mi) – about a third of the surface of Africa – has a coastline of 32,000 km (20,000 mi).
[src:africa/africa-p02] From the most northerly point, Ras ben Sakka in Tunisia (37°21' N), to the most southerly point, Cape Agulhas in South Africa (34°51'15" S), is a distance of approximately 8,000 km (5,000 mi).
[src:africa/africa-p02] Cape Verde, 17°33'22" W, the westernmost point, is a distance of approximately 7,400 km (4,600 mi) to Ras Hafun, 51°27'52" E, the most easterly projection that neighbours Cape Guardafui, the tip of the Horn of Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa's largest country is Algeria, and its smallest country is Seychelles, an archipelago off the east coast.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The smallest nation on the continental mainland is The Gambia.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The African plate, also known as the Nubian plate, is a major tectonic plate that includes most of the continent of Africa (except for its easternmost part) and the adjacent oceanic crust to the west and south.
[src:africa/africa-p02] It also includes a narrow strip of Western Asia along the Mediterranean Sea, including much of Israel, Palestine and Lebanon.
[src:africa/africa-p02] It is bounded by the North American plate and South American plate to the west (separated by the Mid-Atlantic Ridge); the Arabian plate and Somali plate to the east; the Eurasian plate, Aegean Sea plate and Anatolian plate to the north; and the Antarctic plate to the south.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Between 60 million years ago and 10 million years ago, the Somali plate began rifting from the African plate along the East African Rift.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Since the continent of Africa consists of crust from both the African and the Somali plates, some literature refers to the African plate as the *Nubian plate* to distinguish it from the continent as a whole.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The climate of Africa ranges from tropical to subarctic on its highest peaks.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Its northern half is primarily desert, or arid, while its central and southern areas contain both savanna plains and dense jungle (rainforest) regions.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In between, there is a convergence, where vegetation patterns such as sahel and steppe dominate.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa is the hottest continent on Earth and 60% of the entire land surface consists of drylands and deserts.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The record for the highest-ever recorded temperature, in Libya in 1922 (58 °C (136 °F)), was discredited in 2013.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Climate change in Africa is a serious threat because the continent is one of the most vulnerable regions to the effects of climate change, despite being responsible for less than 4% of global greenhouse emissions.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Climate change is causing increasingly erratic rainfall patterns, more frequent extreme weather events such as droughts, floods, and rising sea-surface temperatures across the continent.
[src:africa/africa-p02] These changes threaten food and water security, biodiversity, public health, and economic development.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa is currently warming faster than the rest of the world on average.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Climate change intensifies existing socioeconomic vulnerabilities.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Large segments of the African population depend on climate-sensitive livelihoods such as agriculture (55 - 62% of the workforce in sub-Saharan Africa) and already live in poverty, heightening their exposure to shocks.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Health outcomes worsen as heat stress, vector-borne diseases (such as malaria and dengue), and malnutrition become more prevalent.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Over half (56%) of the over 2,000 recorded public health incidents in Africa between 2001 and 2021 were connected to climate change.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Resource scarcity contributes to displacement and conflict, particularly in fragile regions.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Urban areas, often characterized by informal settlements, face heightened risks from flooding and extreme heat.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa has over 3,000 protected areas, with 198 marine protected areas, 50 biosphere reserves, and 80 wetlands reserves.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Significant habitat destruction, increases in human population and poaching are reducing Africa's biological diversity and arable land.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Human encroachment, civil unrest and the introduction of non-native species threaten biodiversity in Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] This has been exacerbated by administrative problems, inadequate personnel and funding problems.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Deforestation is affecting Africa at twice the world rate, according to the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).
[src:africa/africa-p02] The deforestation rate of 4.08 million hectares in 2000–2015 declined to 3.45 million ha per year in 2015–2025.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Some sources claim that approximately 90% of the original, virgin forests in West Africa have been destroyed.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Over 90% of Madagascar's original forests have been destroyed since the arrival of humans 2000 years ago.
[src:africa/africa-p02] About 65% of Africa's agricultural land suffers from soil degradation.
[src:africa/africa-p02] It is also home to a variety of "jungle" animals including snakes and primates and aquatic life such as crocodiles and amphibians.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In addition, Africa has the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:africa/africa-p02] African environmental problems are problems caused by the direct and indirect human impacts on the natural environment and affect humans and nearly all forms of life in Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Issues include deforestation, soil degradation, air pollution, water pollution, coastal erosion, garbage pollution, climate change, Oil spills, Biodiversity loss, and water scarcity (resulting in problems with access to safe water supply and sanitation).
[src:africa/africa-p02] These issues result in environmental conflict and are connected to broader social struggles for democracy and sovereignty.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The scarcity of climate adaptation techniques in Africa makes it the least resilient continent to climate change.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The African Union (AU) is a continental union consisting of 55 member states.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The union was formed, with Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, as its headquarters, on 26 June 2001.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The union was officially established on 9 July 2002 as a successor to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
[src:africa/africa-p02] In July 2004, the African Union's Pan-African Parliament (PAP) was relocated to Midrand, in South Africa, but the African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights remained in Addis Ababa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The African Union, not to be confused with the AU Commission, is formed by the Constitutive Act of the African Union, which aims to transform the African Economic Community, a federated commonwealth, into a state under established international conventions.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The African Union has a parliamentary government, known as the African Union Government, consisting of legislative, judicial and executive organs.
[src:africa/africa-p02] It is led by the African Union President and Head of State, who is also the President of the Pan-African Parliament.
[src:africa/africa-p02] A person becomes AU President by being elected to the PAP, and subsequently gaining majority support in the PAP.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The government of the AU consists of all-union, regional, state, and municipal authorities, as well as hundreds of institutions, that together manage the day-to-day affairs of the institution.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Extensive human rights abuses still occur in several parts of Africa, often under the oversight of the state.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Most of such violations occur for political reasons, often as a side effect of civil war.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Countries where major human rights violations have been reported in recent times include the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Sudan, Zimbabwe, and Ivory Coast.
[src:africa/africa-p02] African nations have made great efforts to respect international borders as inviolate for a long time.
[src:africa/africa-p02] For example, the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which was established in 1963 and replaced by the African Union in 2002, set the respect for the territorial integrity of each country as one of its principles in OAU Charter.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Indeed, compared with the formation of European countries, there have been fewer international conflicts in Africa for changing the borders, which has influenced country formation there and has enabled some countries to survive that might have been defeated and absorbed by others.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Yet international conflicts have played out by support for proxy armies or rebel movements.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Many states have experienced civil wars: including Rwanda, Sudan, Angola, Sierra Leone, Congo, Liberia, Ethiopia and Somalia.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Wars of national liberation also often took up a Marxist, Marxist–Leninist, or Maoist character in ideological terms, where the independence of African nations was raised in Marxian terms.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Early examples included the Union of the Peoples of Cameroon armed movement against French colonialism, a Marxist–Leninist insurgency, followed by similar movements in Congo (the Simba Rebellion).
[src:africa/africa-p02] Che Guevara participated in the latter, and opined in 1967 that Africa was not ready for revolution.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Despite this, in Zanzibar before and after unification with Tanzania, forms of socialism took hold.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Even after 1990, there are some examples of Military Marxism, such as a militia established by Ernest Wamba-dia-Wamba in Eastern Congo in the 1990s.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The countries in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations, and data included are per sources in cross-referenced articles.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Where they differ, provisos are clearly indicated.
[src:africa/africa-p02] This list contains nine territories that are administered as incorporated areas of a primarily non-African country but that belong geographically to the African continent.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The continent's total nominal GDP remains behind that of several individual countries, including the United States, China, Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, India and France.
[src:africa/africa-p02] According to the United Nations' Human Development Report in 2003, the bottom 24 ranked nations (151st to 175th) were all African.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, inadequate water supply and sanitation, and poor health affect a large proportion of the people who reside on the African continent.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In August 2008, the World Bank announced revised global poverty estimates based on a new international poverty line of $1.25 per day (versus the previous measure of $1.00).
[src:africa/africa-p02] Eighty-one percent of the sub-Saharan African population was living on less than $2.50 (PPP) per day in 2005, compared with 86% for India.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa is the least successful region of the world in reducing poverty ($1.25 per day); some 50% of the population living in poverty in 1981 (200 million people), a figure that rose to 58% in 1996 before dropping to 50% in 2005 (380 million people).
[src:africa/africa-p02] The average poor person in sub-Saharan Africa is estimated to live on only 70 cents per day, and was poorer in 2003 than in 1973, indicating increasing poverty in some areas.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Some of it is attributed to unsuccessful economic liberalisation programmes spearheaded by foreign companies and governments, but other studies have cited bad domestic government policies more than external factors.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa is now at risk of being in debt once again, particularly in sub-Saharan African countries.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The last debt crisis in 2005 was resolved with help from the heavily indebted poor countries scheme (HIPC).
[src:africa/africa-p02] The HIPC resulted in some positive and negative effects on the economy in Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] About ten years after the 2005 debt crisis in sub-Saharan Africa was resolved, Zambia fell back into debt.
[src:africa/africa-p02] A small reason was due to the fall in copper prices in 2011, but the bigger reason was that a large amount of the money Zambia borrowed was wasted or pocketed by the elite.
[src:africa/africa-p02] From 1995 to 2005, Africa's rate of economic growth increased, averaging 5% in 2005.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Some countries experienced still higher growth rates, notably Angola, Sudan and Equatorial Guinea, all of which had recently begun extracting their petroleum reserves or had expanded their oil extraction capacity.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The following table shows the projected nominal GDP and GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in 2026 by the IMF.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The continent is believed to hold 90% of the world's cobalt, 90% of its platinum, 50% of its gold, 98% of its chromium, 70% of its tantalite, 64% of its manganese and one-third of its uranium.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has 70% of the world's coltan, a mineral used in the production of tantalum capacitors for electronic devices such as cell phones.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The DRC also has more than 30% of the world's diamond reserves.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Guinea is the world's largest exporter of bauxite.
[src:africa/africa-p02] As the growth in Africa has been driven mainly by services and not manufacturing or agriculture, it has been growth without jobs and without reduction in poverty levels.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In fact, the food security crisis of 2008, which took place following the global financial crisis, pushed 100 million people into food insecurity.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In 2024 nearly 307 million people in Africa were undernourished (46% of the global total), an increase of 10 million people since 2023 and 34 million from 2022.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In recent years, China has built increasingly stronger ties with African nations and is Africa's largest trading partner.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In 2007, Chinese companies invested a total of US$1 billion in Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] A Harvard University study led by professor Calestous Juma showed that Africa could feed itself by making the transition from importer to self-sufficiency.
[src:africa/africa-p02] "African agriculture is at the crossroads; we have come to the end of a century of policies that favoured Africa's export of raw materials and importation of food.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Cooking with biogas in Tanzania; Geothermal energy infrastructure in Kenya; Coal power station in South Africa; Solar-powered lamp-light in Zambia.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Energy in Africa is characterised by low per-capita consumption and limited access to modern energy services, reflecting both infrastructural and socio-economic challenges across the continent.
[src:africa/africa-p02] As of 2023, Africa accounted for just 5.5% of global total final energy consumption, with per-capita energy use more than three times lower than the global average.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The energy mix is dominated by biofuels and waste, which make up 43% of total final consumption, primarily for household cooking and heating, followed by oil products at 33%, electricity at 11%, natural gas at 9%, and coal at 4%.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Electricity access remains a major challenge, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 450 million rural residents lack reliable electricity, and grid coverage is often inconsistent.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Clean cooking solutions are similarly underdeveloped, leaving over 900 million people reliant on polluting fuels such as firewood, charcoal, and agricultural residues, which disproportionately affect women and children.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Transport energy is dominated by oil products, reflecting low motorisation rates and limited adoption of electric mobility, although countries such as Ethiopia, Morocco, and Egypt have begun adopting policies to reduce fossil fuel dependency.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa possesses some of the world's most abundant energy resources, including oil, natural gas, coal, hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and biomass, much of which remains underutilised.
[src:africa/africa-p02] While fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas continue to dominate energy production and electricity generation in Africa, renewable sources are increasingly expanding across the continent.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and modern biomass are growing in capacity, though their deployment remains uneven and limited compared to the continent's vast potential.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Hydropower is the largest non-combustible renewable source, while solar energy offers immense potential due to high irradiation levels, particularly in the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:africa/africa-p02] There are regional differences: North Africa is dominated by oil and gas production, Southern Africa by coal and hydropower, East Africa by hydropower and geothermal, and West and Central Africa face major electrification gaps despite hydroelectric potential.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Water development and management are complex in Africa due to the multiplicity of trans-boundary water resources (rivers, lakes and aquifers).
[src:africa/africa-p02] Around 75% of sub-Saharan Africa falls within 53 international river basin catchments that traverse multiple borders.
[src:africa/africa-p02] This particular constraint can also be converted into an opportunity if the potential for trans-boundary cooperation is harnessed in the development of the area's water resources.
[src:africa/africa-p02] A multi-sectoral analysis of the Zambezi River, for example, shows that riparian cooperation could lead to a 23% increase in firm energy production without any additional investments.
[src:africa/africa-p02] A number of institutional and legal frameworks for transboundary cooperation exist, such as the Zambezi River Authority, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Protocol, Volta River Authority and the Nile Basin Commission.
[src:africa/africa-p02] However, additional efforts are required to further develop political will, as well as the financial capacities and institutional frameworks needed for win-win multilateral cooperative actions and optimal solutions for all riparians.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa is considered by anthropologists to be the most genetically diverse continent as a result of being the longest inhabited.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa's population has rapidly increased over the last 40 years, and is consequently relatively young.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In some African states, more than half the population is under 25 years of age.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The total number of people in Africa increased from 229 million in 1950 to 630 million in 1990.
[src:africa/africa-p02] As of 2021, the population of Africa is estimated at 1,394 million.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa's total population surpassing other continents is fairly recent; African population surpassed Europe in the 1990s, while the Americas was overtaken sometime around the year 2000.
[src:africa/africa-p02] This increase in number of babies born in Africa compared to the rest of the world is expected to reach approximately 37% in the year 2050; while in 1990 sub-Saharan Africa accounted for only 16% of the world's births.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The total fertility rate (children per woman) for Sub-Saharan Africa is 4.7 as of 2018, the highest in the world.
[src:africa/africa-p02] All countries in sub-Saharan Africa had TFRs (average number of children) above replacement level in 2019 and accounted for 27.1% of global livebirths.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In 2021, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 29% of global births.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Speakers of Bantu languages (part of the Niger–Congo family) are the majority in southern, central and southeast Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The Bantu-speaking peoples from the Sahel progressively expanded over most of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] But there are also several Nilotic groups in South Sudan and East Africa, the mixed Swahili people on the Swahili Coast, and a few remaining indigenous Khoisan ("San" or "Bushmen") and Pygmy peoples in Southern and Central Africa, respectively.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Bantu-speaking Africans also predominate in Gabon and Equatorial Guinea, and are found in parts of southern Cameroon.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In the Kalahari Desert of Southern Africa, the distinct people known as the Bushmen (also "San", closely related to, but distinct from "Hottentots") have long been present.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The San are physically distinct from other Africans and are the indigenous people of southern Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Pygmies are the pre-Bantu indigenous peoples of central Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The peoples of West Africa primarily speak Niger–Congo languages, belonging mostly to its non-Bantu branches, though some Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic speaking groups are also found.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The Niger–Congo-speaking Yoruba, Igbo, Fulani, Akan, and Wolof ethnic groups are the largest and most influential.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In the central Sahara, Mandinka or Mande groups are most significant.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Chadic-speaking groups, including the Hausa, are found in more northerly parts of the region nearest to the Sahara, and Nilo-Saharan communities, such as the Songhai, Kanuri, and Zarma, are found in the eastern parts of West Africa bordering Central Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The peoples of North Africa consist of three main indigenous groups: Berbers in the northwest, Egyptians in the northeast, and Nilo-Saharan-speaking peoples in the east.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The Arabs who arrived in the 7th century AD introduced the Arabic language and Islam to North Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The Semitic Phoenicians (who founded Carthage) and Hyksos, the Indo-Iranian Alans, the Indo-European Greeks, Romans, and Vandals settled in North Africa as well.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Significant Berber communities remain within Morocco and Algeria in the 21st century, while, to a lesser extent, Berber speakers are also present in some regions of Tunisia and Libya.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The Berber-speaking Tuareg and other often-nomadic peoples are the principal inhabitants of the Saharan interior of North Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In Mauritania, there is a small but near-extinct Berber community in the north and Niger–Congo-speaking peoples in the south, though in both regions Arabic and Arab culture predominates.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In Sudan, although Arabic and Arab culture predominate, it is mostly inhabited by groups that originally spoke Nilo-Saharan, such as the Nubians, Fur, Masalit and Zaghawa, who, over the centuries, have variously intermixed with migrants from the Arabian peninsula.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Small communities of Afro-Asiatic-speaking Beja nomads can also be found in Egypt and Sudan.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In the Horn of Africa, some Ethiopian and Eritrean groups (like the Amhara and Tigrayans, collectively known as Habesha) speak languages from the Semitic branch of the Afro-Asiatic language family, while the Oromo and Somali speak languages from the Cushitic branch of Afro-Asiatic.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Prior to the decolonisation movements of the post-World War II era, Europeans were represented in every part of Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Decolonization during the 1960s and 1970s often resulted in the mass emigration of white settlers—especially from Algeria and Morocco (1.6 million *pieds-noirs* in North Africa), Kenya, Congo, Rhodesia, Mozambique and Angola.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Between 1975 and 1977, over a million colonials returned to Portugal alone.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Nevertheless, white Africans remain an important minority in many African states, particularly Zimbabwe, Namibia, Réunion, and South Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The country with the largest white African population is South Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Dutch and British diasporas represent the largest communities of European ancestry on the continent today.
[src:africa/africa-p02] European colonisation also brought sizable groups of Asians, particularly from the Indian subcontinent, to British colonies.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Large Indian communities are found in South Africa, and smaller ones are present in Kenya, Tanzania, and some other southern and southeast African countries.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The large Indian community in Uganda was expelled by the dictator Idi Amin in 1972, though many have since returned.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The islands in the Indian Ocean are also populated primarily by people of Asian origin, often mixed with Africans and Europeans.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The Malagasy people of Madagascar are an Austronesian people, but those along the coast are generally mixed with Bantu, Arab, Indian and European origins.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Malay and Indian ancestries are also important components in the group of people known in South Africa as Cape Coloureds (people with origins in two or more races and continents).
[src:africa/africa-p02] During the 20th century, small but economically important communities of Lebanese have also developed in the larger coastal cities of West and East Africa, respectively.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The Sahara served as a trans-regional passageway and place of dwelling for people in Africa during various humid phases and periods throughout the history of Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] As early as 11,000 years ago, Sub-Saharan West Africans, bearing macrohaplogroup L (e.g., L1b1a11, L1b1a6a, L1b1a8, L1b1a9a1, L2a1k, L3d1b1a), may have migrated through North Africa and into Europe, mostly into southern Europe (e.g., Iberia).
[src:africa/africa-p02] The genetic marker E1b1 was identified to have wide distribution across Egypt, with "P2/215/M35.1 (E1b1b), for short M35, likely also originated in eastern tropical Africa, and is predominantly distributed in an arc from the Horn of Africa up through Egypt".
[src:africa/africa-p02] The R haplogroup has also been identified to have high frequencies in central Saharan Africa, among some Afro-Asiatic and Nilo-Saharan language speaking groups.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Genetic evidence has identified the Horn of Africa to be the source of a genetic marker "M35/215" Y-chromosome lineage for a significant population component which moved north from that region into Egypt and the Levant.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Historian Christopher Ehret argued that this genetic distribution paralleled the spread of the Afrasian language family with the movement of people from the Horn of Africa into Egypt and added a new demic component to the existing population of Egypt 17,000 years ago.
[src:africa/africa-p02] According to a recent study, the Arab migrations to the Maghreb was mainly a demographic process that heavily implied gene flow and remodelled the genetic structure of the Maghreb region in North Africa, rather than a mere cultural replacement as claimed by older studies.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Another study found out that the majority of J-M267 (Eu10) chromosomes in the Maghreb are due to the recent gene flow caused by the Arab migrations to the Maghreb in the first millennium CE as both southern Qahtanite and northern Adnanite Arabs added to the heterogenous Maghrebi ethnic melting pot.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The Eu10 chromosome pool in the Maghreb is derived not only from early Neolithic dispersions from Western Asia but to a much greater extent from recent expansions of Arab tribes from the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:africa/africa-p02] David Schoenbrun, Christopher Ehret, Steven A.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Brandt and Shomarka Keita (2025) have highlighted the problematic categorisation of genetic haplogroups characterised as ‘African’ and ‘Eurasian' in North African genome studies.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In reference to the van de Loosdrecht et al.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In their view, identifying a range of African populations may still remain an issue “since the idea of ‘African’ still gets stereotyped or restricted.
[src:africa/africa-p02] (Accepting the southwestern Asian/Levantine geographical continuity with Africa eliminates a conceptual barrier related to racio-typological thinking permitting an Africasian construct analogous to Eurasian.)”.
[src:africa/africa-p02] While Africans profess a wide variety of religious beliefs, the majority of the people respect African religions or parts of them.
[src:africa/africa-p02] However, in formal surveys or census, most people will identify with major religions that came from outside the continent, mainly through colonisation.
[src:africa/africa-p02] There are several reasons for this, the main one being the colonial idea that African religious beliefs and practices are not good enough.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Religious beliefs and statistics on religious affiliation are difficult to come by since they are often a sensitive topic for governments with mixed religious populations.
[src:africa/africa-p02] According to the *World Book Encyclopedia*, Islam and Christianity are the two largest religions in Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Islam is most prevalent in Northern Africa, and is the state religion of many North African countries, such as Algeria, where 99% of the population practices Islam.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The majority of people in most governments in Southern, Southeast, and Central Africa, as well as in a sizable portion of the Horn of Africa and West Africa, identify as Christians.
[src:africa/africa-p02] The Coptic Christians constitute a sizable minority in Egypt, and the Ethiopian Orthodox Church is the largest church in Ethiopia, with 36 million and 51 million adherents.
[src:africa/africa-p02] According to Encyclopædia Britannica, 45% of the population are Christians, 40% are Muslims, and 10% follow traditional religions.
[src:africa/africa-p02] A small number of Africans are Hindu, Buddhist, Confucianist, Baháʼí, or Jewish.
[src:africa/africa-p02] There is also a minority of people in Africa who are irreligious.
[src:africa/africa-p02] By most estimates, well over a thousand languages (UNESCO has estimated around two thousand) are spoken in Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Most are of African origin, though some are of European or Asian origin.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Africa is the most multilingual continent in the world, and it is not rare for individuals to fluently speak not only multiple African languages, but one or more European ones as well.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Following the end of colonialism, nearly all African countries adopted official languages that originated outside the continent, although several countries also granted legal recognition to indigenous languages (such as Swahili, Yoruba, Igbo and Hausa).
[src:africa/africa-p02] In numerous countries, English and French (*see African French*) are used for communication in the public sphere such as government, commerce, education and the media.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Arabic, Portuguese, Afrikaans and Spanish are examples of languages that trace their origin to outside of Africa, and that are used by millions of Africans today, both in the public and private spheres.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Italian is spoken by some in former Italian colonies in Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p02] German is spoken in Namibia, as it was a former German protectorate.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In total, at least a fifth of Africans speak the former colonial languages.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Moreover, in recent years some African countries have been considering removing their official former colonial languages, such as Mali, Burkina Faso and Niger which removed French as an official language in the 2020s in favour of native languages, while also renaming colonial street names.
[src:africa/africa-p02] More than 85% of individuals in Africa use traditional medicine as an alternative to often expensive allopathic medical health care and costly pharmaceutical products.
[src:africa/africa-p02] AIDS in post-colonial Africa is a prevalent issue.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Although the continent is home to about 15.2 percent of the world's population, more than two-thirds of the total infected worldwide—some 35 million people—were Africans, of whom 15 million have already died.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa alone accounted for an estimated 69 percent of all people living with HIV and 70 percent of all AIDS deaths in 2011.
[src:africa/africa-p02] In the countries of sub-Saharan Africa most affected, AIDS has raised death rates and lowered life expectancy among adults between the ages of 20 and 49 by about twenty years.
[src:africa/africa-p02] Furthermore, the life expectancy in many parts of Africa has declined, largely as a result of the HIV/AIDS epidemic with life-expectancy in some countries reaching as low as thirty-four years.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Africa is divided into a great number of ethnic cultures.
[src:africa/africa-p03] In recent times, the call for a much greater emphasis on the cultural dimension in all aspects of development has become increasingly vocal.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Some aspects of traditional African cultures have become less practised in recent years as a result of neglect and suppression by colonial and post-colonial regimes.
[src:africa/africa-p03] For example, African customs were discouraged, and African languages were prohibited in mission schools, while colonialists such as Leopold II of Belgium attempted to "civilize" Africans by discouraging polygamy and witchcraft.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Abiola Irele and Simon Gikandi comment that the current identity of African literature had its genesis in the "traumatic encounter between Africa and Europe".
[src:africa/africa-p03] On the other hand, Mhoze Chikowero believes that Africans deployed music, dance, spirituality, and other performative cultures to (re)assert themselves as active agents and indigenous intellectuals, to unmake their colonial marginalisation and reshape their own destinies.
[src:africa/africa-p03] As of March 2023, 98 African properties are listed by UNESCO as World Heritage Sites.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Among these proprieties, 54 are cultural sites, 39 are natural sites and 5 are mixed sites.
[src:africa/africa-p03] The List of World Heritage in Danger includes 15 African sites.
[src:africa/africa-p03] African art refers to works of visual art, including works of sculpture, painting, metalwork, and pottery, originating from the various peoples of the African continent and influenced by distinct, indigenous traditions of aesthetic expression.
[src:africa/africa-p03] While the various artistic traditions of such a large and diverse continent display considerable regional and cultural variety, there are consistent artistic themes, recurring motifs, and unifying elements across the broad spectrum of the African visual expression.
[src:africa/africa-p03] As is the case for every artistic tradition in human history, African art was created within specific social, political, and religious contexts.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Likewise, African art was often created not purely for art's sake, but rather with some practical, spiritual, and/or didactic purpose in mind.
[src:africa/africa-p03] In general, African art prioritizes conceptual and symbolic representation over realism, aiming to visualize the subject's spiritual essence.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Ethiopian art, heavily influenced by Ethiopia's long-standing Christian tradition, is also different from most African art, where Traditional African religion (with Islam prevalent in the north east and north west presently) was dominant until the 20th century.
[src:africa/africa-p03] African art includes prehistoric and ancient art, the Islamic art of West Africa, the Christian art of East Africa, and the traditional artifacts of these and other regions.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Many African sculptures were historically made of wood and other natural materials that have not survived from earlier than a few centuries ago, although rare older pottery and metal figures can be found in some areas.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Some of the earliest decorative objects, such as shell beads and evidence of paint, have been discovered in Africa, dating to the Middle Stone Age.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Masks are important elements in the art of many people, along with human figures, and are often highly stylized.
[src:africa/africa-p03] There exist diverse styles, which can often be observed within a single context of origin and may be influenced by the intended use of the object.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Nevertheless, broad regional trends are discernible.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Sculpture is most common among "groups of settled cultivators in the areas drained by the Niger and Congo rivers" in West Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Direct images of deities are relatively infrequent, but masks in particular are or were often made for ritual ceremonies.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Since the late 19th century, there has been an increasing amount of African art in Western collections, the finest pieces of which are displayed as part of the history of colonization.
[src:africa/africa-p03] African art had an important influence on European Modernist art, which was inspired by their interest in abstract depiction.
[src:africa/africa-p03] It was this appreciation of African sculpture that has been attributed to the very concept of "African art", as seen by European and American artists and art historians.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Obidoh Freeborn posits that colonialism is one element that has created the character of modern African art.
[src:africa/africa-p03] According to authors Douglas Fraser and Herbert M.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Author Chika Okeke-Agulu states that "the racist infrastructure of British imperial enterprise forced upon the political and cultural guardians of empire a denial and suppression of an emergent sovereign Africa and modernist art".
[src:africa/africa-p03] scaling: small parts of the structure tend to look similar to larger parts, such as a circular village made of circular houses.
[src:africa/africa-p03] African architecture in some areas has been influenced by external cultures for centuries, according to available evidence.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Western architecture has influenced coastal areas since the late 15th century and is now an important source of inspiration for many larger buildings, particularly in major cities.
[src:africa/africa-p03] African architecture uses a wide range of materials, including thatch, stick/wood, mud, mudbrick, rammed earth, and stone.
[src:africa/africa-p03] These material preferences vary by region: North Africa for stone and rammed earth, the Horn of Africa for stone and mortar, West Africa for mud/adobe, Central Africa for thatch/wood and more perishable materials, Southeast and Southern Africa for stone and thatch/wood.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Cinema of Africa refers to the film industries and films produced in the continent of Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p03] It covers both the history and present of the making or screening of films on the African continent, and also refers to the persons involved in this form of audiovisual culture.
[src:africa/africa-p03] It dates back to the late 19th century, when film reels were the primary cinematic technology in use.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Cairo has been the capital of film industry in Africa since the early 20th century to the present day.
[src:africa/africa-p03] As there are more than 50 countries with audiovisual traditions, there is no one single 'African cinema'.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Both historically and culturally, there are major regional differences between North African and sub-Saharan cinemas, and between the cinemas of different countries.
[src:africa/africa-p03] The Egyptian film industry and the Tunisian are also among the oldest in the world.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Cinema of Egypt in particular is the most established and flourishing industry in Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Pioneers Auguste and Louis Lumière screened their films in Alexandria, Cairo, Tunis, Susa, Libya and Hammam-Lif, Tunisia in 1896.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Albert Samama Chikly is often cited as the first producer of indigenous African cinema, screening his own short documentaries in the casino of Tunis as early as December 1905.
[src:africa/africa-p03] The continent of Africa and its music is vast and highly diverse, with different regions and nations maintaining distinct musical traditions.
[src:africa/africa-p03] African music includes genres such as makwaya, highlife, mbube, township music, jùjú, fuji, jaiva, afrobeat, afrofusion, mbalax, Congolese rumba, soukous, ndombolo, makossa, kizomba, and taarab, among others.
[src:africa/africa-p03] African music also uses a wide variety of instruments from across the continent.
[src:africa/africa-p03] The music and dance traditions of the African diaspora, shaped to varying degrees by African musical traditions, include American genres such as Dixieland jazz, blues, and jazz, as well as Caribbean styles such as calypso (see kaiso), and soca.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Latin American music genres including cumbia, salsa, son cubano, rumba, conga, bomba, samba, and zouk developed from the music of enslaved Africans and have, in turn, influenced contemporary African popular music.
[src:africa/africa-p03] African dance (also Afro dance, Afrodance and Afro-dance) refers to the various dance styles of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:africa/africa-p03] These dances are closely connected with the traditional rhythms and music traditions of the region.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Music and dancing is an integral part of many traditional African societies.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Songs and dances facilitate teaching and promoting social values, the celebration of special events and major life milestones, the performance of oral history and other recitations, and spiritual experiences.
[src:africa/africa-p03] African dance uses the concepts of polyrhythm and total body articulation.
[src:africa/africa-p03] African dances are often a collective activity performed in large groups, with significant interaction between dancers and onlookers.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Fifty-four African countries have football teams in the Confederation of African Football.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Egypt has won the African Cup seven times, and a record-making three times in a row.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Cameroon, Nigeria, Morocco, Senegal, Ghana, and Algeria have advanced to the knockout stage of recent FIFA World Cups.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Morocco, at the 2022 World Cup in Qatar was the first African nation to reach the semi-finals of the FIFA Men's World Cup.
[src:africa/africa-p03] South Africa hosted the 2010 World Cup tournament, becoming the first African country to do so.
[src:africa/africa-p03] The top clubs in each African football league play the CAF Champions League, while lower-ranked clubs compete in CAF Confederation Cup.
[src:africa/africa-p03] In recent years, the continent has progressed in terms of state-of-the-art basketball facilities, which have been built in cities such as Cairo, Dakar, Johannesburg, Kigali, Luanda, and Rades.
[src:africa/africa-p03] The number of African basketball players who drafted into the U.S.
[src:africa/africa-p03] NBA has experienced growth in the 2010s.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Cricket is popular in some African nations.
[src:africa/africa-p03] South Africa and Zimbabwe have Test status, while Kenya is the leading non-test team and previously had One-Day International cricket (ODI) status (from 10 October 1997, until 30 January 2014).
[src:africa/africa-p03] The three countries jointly hosted the 2003 Cricket World Cup.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Namibia is the other African country to have played in a World Cup.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Morocco, in northern Africa, hosted the 2002 Morocco Cup, but the national team has never qualified for a major tournament.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Rugby is popular in several southern African nations.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Namibia and Zimbabwe have appeared on multiple occasions at the Rugby World Cup, while South Africa is the most successful national team at the Rugby World Cup, having won the tournament on four occasions, in 1995, 2007, 2019, and 2023.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Traditional sports were strictly marginalised during the colonial era, and many are dying or have gone extinct under the pressure of modernisation, however lots remain popular despite not having formal governmental recognition or support.
[src:africa/africa-p03] Some examples are Senegalese wrestling, Dambe, Nguni stick-fighting, and Savika.
[src:africa/aziziya] According to the Köppen climate classification, ʽAziziya has a borderline hot semi-arid climate (*BSh*) immediately bordering a hot desert climate (*BWh*).
[src:africa/aziziya] On 13 September 1922, a high temperature of 58.0 °C (136.4 °F) was recorded in ʽAziziya.
[src:africa/aziziya] This was long considered the highest temperature ever measured on Earth; however, this record was deemed illegitimate in 2012 after an investigation by the World Meteorological Organization (WMO).
[src:africa/aziziya] Shortly before the record reading on 13 September 1922, the weather station's usual maximum thermometer had been damaged and then replaced by an uncalibrated, ordinary maximum-minimum thermometer of the kind often used in greenhouses.
[src:africa/aziziya] On 11 September 1922, the usual record keeper was replaced by an inexperienced observer, who was untrained in the use of the thermometer and the record log.
[src:africa/aziziya] This is known by the change in handwriting on the log sheets and by the high and low temperatures being recorded in the wrong columns.
[src:africa/aziziya] The thermometer used sliding colored cylinders to record maximum and minimum temperatures, and these cylinders were about 7 to 8 degrees Celsius long on the thermometer scale.
[src:africa/aziziya] The WMO now believes that the inexperienced observer was reading from the wrong end of the high-temperature cylinder inside the thermometer, getting a reading which was 7 to 8 degrees too high.
[src:africa/aziziya] On 13 September 2012, the WMO announced that their Commission of Climatology World Archive of Weather and Climate Extremes had found that the record was invalid.
[src:africa/aziziya] As such, the world record for hottest temperature is now 56.7 °C (134.1 °F), recorded on 10 July 1913 at Greenland Ranch in Death Valley, California in the United States.
